deck_excerpt: Live☆Twins deck, without being just an engine.
deck_description: Live☆Twins are an archetype based around the twins, Lil-la and Ki-sikil, who special summon each other mainly aim to get their link monster counterparts on the field. It's a good engine for link summoning since most the time you don't need to search out a Ki-sikil or Lil-la (as they can special summon each other from the deck, aside from Treat and Frost). The idea for this deck is to get as many materials on the field as possible and have enough to special summon their Evil★Twin link monsters. Both Evil★Twin links summon the other from the graveyard, so if one is taken out, you can immediately special summon the other from the graveyard and get effects based on which was special summoned that way. I will not be covering any staples in the deck (Maxx "C", Ash Blossom, Nibiru, Triple Tactics, Effect Veiler, etc.). This deck is a bit tricky to play, you have to bait your opponent out (which you should mostly always be doing) in order to make them use their effects and/or to see what they have (in this case, hand traps). Although it's not the end of the world if you Ki-sikil or Lil-la's searcher effect is negated, it does stop you from having another body on the field. Monsters: Live☆Twin Ki-sikil / Lil-La - These 2 are the main searchers in the deck, you'll always want at least one of these in the hand, as when one is normal or special summoned while you have no monsters on the field, you can special summon their twin counterpart (if you normal summon Lil-la, you'll get Si-sikil and vice versa). Their life burn and gain effects are mostly secondary as you won't really have these on the field most of the time outside of when you need to link summon. Live☆Twin Treat / Frost - If you have a Lil-la or Ki-sikil on the field, you can special summon them based on which of the twins are on the field (Ex: if you have a Ki-sikil, you'll summon a Treat). These are the ideal targets for being sent to the GY as either link material or for a discard (Ex: using Live☆Twin Home), and they both have GY effects. Frost banishes itself when your opponent draws a card, you draw a card. Treat banishes itself when someone takes damage involving a Evil★Twin monster Evil★Twins Ki-sikil and Lil-la - The main boss (aside from Sunny, which is not in at the moment), her main destructive effect can be pretty great at breaking boards (she makes it so your opponent has to send every card they control to the GY, until they have just 2). Although that effect isn't bad, the main point of her is to either be a discard (since she can special summon herself from the GY by using 2 link monsters) and to be a big beatstick (if you have a Ki-sikil or Lil-la in your GY (which you almost always will), she gains 2200 ATK and DEF, making her 4400 ATK/DEF). Honest / Dark Honest - You can swap these out for something else, but for the most part, these cards can win you the game depending on how they're used. Best used if you have a Treat in the GY, so when they swing into you, you can use either Honest, banish Treat, and then decrease the attack of 1 other monster by that amount. You can swap the Dark Honest for Honest, but this deck is primarily dark monsters so that's what I put in. Spells: Forbidden Droplet - I know this is a staple, but it works extremely well in this deck, especially since neither Evil★Twin or Live☆Twin has any real attack power, outside of Evil★Twin's boss monster. Negating effects and halving the enemies attack power is great, especially if you have a Lil-la Treat in the GY and can swing over enemies (it can also stop spells/traps making it a pretty vital card in a deck with little-to-no negating effects). Secret Password - The 2nd main searcher for the deck, this searches out for either twins spells and traps (or if you have a Ki-sikil and Lil-la on the field, you can add the Evil★Twin boss monster to your hand. This will be your main "bait" card, mainly for Ash Blossom, as most of the time you'll have either a Ki-sikil or Lil-la (or more) in hand. Ideally you'll search out a Live☆Twin Sunny's Snitch (which I'll explain below). Live☆Twin Sunny's Snitch - The main searcher for the deck, it allows you to search for one Live☆Twin monster (you can choose what to add to your hand depending on what you have in-hand. If you want reassurance on the next turn, you can always search out a Lil-la or Ki-sikil, though if you want more link materials on board, you can search out a Frost or Treat (which if you plan on linking, is a good idea). Live☆Twin Home - Home is a decent card for the most part, but it depends on what you have in-hand, I only put it at 1 because it's searchable with 'Secret Password' and because it's usually not needed as most of the time you'll have ways to special summon the twins. This can come in clutch if you really need it to, though, so I'd recommend at least having it. Sending 'Evil★Twins Ki-sikil and Lil-la' to the GY with it's effect is the best case scenario (but don't count on it unless you plan on drawing it or plan on searching it with no interruptions). Extra deck: Evil★Twin Ki-sikil - You'll be seeing this and Lil-la's link monster quite a lot, as with one you get the other. Ideally if you're going first, this is the first card you link into, because whichever of the twins you link into first, will be the one that's last on the field, and whose effect will activate. When she's special summoned and you have a Lil-la monster on the field, you can draw one card (usually that'll be her link counterpart). If you have don't have a Lil-la on the field,  you can special summon one Lil-la from the GY. Evil★Twin Lil-la - Lil-la is the same as 'Evil★Twin Ki-sikil', except for a few things; if you have a Ki-sikil on the field, you can destroy 1 card on the field (this does target), and if you don't have a Ki-sikil on the field, you can special summon one from the GY. I:P Masquerena - She's mainly here as support for any link monster, as she has a quick effect that says you can link using materials you control during your opponent's main phase 1, and when she's used as link material, the monster that was link summoned can't be destroyed by card effects. Accesscode Talker - A great staple for any link deck, when he's link summoned, you can target 1 link monster in your GY and gain attack equal to that link's rating x 1000. He also has the effect of banishing 1 link from your graveyard to destroy 1 card on the field, which is not once per turn. Link Disciple / Link Devotee - I put these together because they're a great pair and because they're cheap. Link summon Disciple and then Devotee underneath, tribute Devotee, you'll then be able to draw 1 card (in which you'll have to put 1 card on the bottom of the deck), and you'll gain 2 Cyberse link materials. Since you won't be able to link into Link-3 or higher for the rest of the turn, if you have a Lil-la or Ki-sikil on board, you can go into their link monsters. You can also go into I:P Masquerena using the two tokens and then into a link-3+ monster next turn (preferably Excode Talker since your twins can also gain ATK and protection), gaining destruction protection. Knightmare Links - I'm grouping all 3 together just for simplicity, they all have pretty self-explanatory effects. To simplify, Phoenix can pop 1 trap/spell on the field, Unicorn can shuffle 1 card on field back into the deck (this targets), and Gryphon can set 1 spell or trap from your GY. They all have effects based on if they're co-linked or not. Underworld Goddess of the Closed World - She has many uses, the main use being able to use 1 monster your opponent controls as materials (bonus points if they're a link monster), she's unaffected by cards, unless they target (so 'Forbidden Droplet', which targets, will not effect her), and she can negate any effect that lets your opponent special summon from the GY, once per turn. Transcode Talker - Transcode is an amazing card in this deck, not only does it provide protection to co-linked monsters and give them a +500 ATK boost, but it can also special summon one Link-3 or lower Cyberse monster from your GY (which most likely would be I:P). Side-deck: You can tech many things in here if you want, such as 'Royal Decree' (which negates all traps on the field) which would work since this deck doesn't really play any traps (aside from Imperm). These are the main ones for me: Parallel eXceed - This is a great option for really any link deck, you can put in 2 or 3 (3 if you want to draw it more) so you basically have 2 free link materials. When you link summon, and eXceed is in your hands, you can special summon it and another (from hand or deck) to the field where the link monster points to. Royal Decree - Royal Decree is a decent option for this deck, as it runs only 2 traps, though do note that it's pretty easy to get off the field since we don't have much of any protection. Tri-Gate Wizard - This link monster is pretty easy to get on the field (even moreso with 'Parallel eXceed') and gains effects based on how many cards are co-linked with it. It can be pretty easy to get on the field and make annoying to get off (with I:P and 'Transcode Talker') Main weaknesses: This archetype doesn't have much of any protection by itself, whether that's negation effects or attack power, so it will have to rely heavily on your other link monsters. By itself, the main idea for the links is to take the damage (or if you used the field spell, which you shouldn't, to negate the attack) and use the effects from the destroyed twins to make sure you last. This deck is very weak to things like 'Necrovalley' (but it does have outs, like 'Feather Duster' and 'Knightmare' links), as they rely heavily on their GY. If your opponent knows your deck, then stopping you can become pretty easy early on (you'll still want to bait anyone out using cards how you see fit). This deck also can have trouble with banishment, though it's still a decent engine to link into other monsters. Getting Started: This deck has many, many combos, and many ways to play, but for the most part, you'll start off with summoning your twins (mainly Ki-sikil and Lil-la, not their Treat or Frost versions) and linking into their links. Whichever link you start with first (unless you have one on the field) you'll end on, so if you link to 'Evil★Twin Ki-sikil', you'll end on 'Evil★Twin Ki-sikil' (which is great for going first, since you get to draw a card). This deck has a lot of drawing power, you can make use of that by baiting some of your opponents with excess cards (or keeping them in hand, up to you), it can make playing a lot smoother. Some of the links (namely 'Devotee' and 'Disciple') make linking that much easier, so you can get out not only your twin links, but a Link-3 (by using I:P next turn) to go into something like 'Tri-Gate Wizard' or 'Transcode Talker' (which can also special summon a Link-3 from the GY). Having access to lots of Link materials means you can also use something like 'Underworld Goddess' to help clear any boss monsters they may have that you can't remove or swing over.

deck_excerpt: One of the most free to play/budget friendly decks in the game, Eldlich Shiranui.
deck_description: Hi, it is I, Grayewick the Fusionist, back with another deck that isn't exactly a Fusion strategy but one that I actually like. Presenting, Eldlich Shiranui. First things first, this is not exactly a meta build, but I gotta say that I'm REALLY impressed on how budget this deck can be built. Playing through the solo mode and finishing the Shiranui portion of it unlocks an almost finished Shiranui core alongside the Secret Pack "Fires of This World and The Next", which allows you to potentially craft the remaining Shiranui monsters and two of the best Zombie support monsters, Gozuki and Mezuki. The only mandatory UR in this build is at least one copy of both Shiranui Sunsaga as your main boss monster, Shiranui Skillsaga Supremacy, and Yuki-Onna, the Absolute Zero Mayakashi, your alternate win condition who's also a semi-floodgate. All of the SR Shiranui monsters are already unlocked for free upon completion, and the Eldlich core can easily be obtainable as well in the Secret Pack "Immortal Royalty" which allows you to also potentially pull Vampire Sucker. Book of Life being just a Rare card as well as Plaguespreader Zombie being a Normal card only actually surprised me in a good way. Other Zombie-type monster supports such as Revived King Ha Des, Red-Eyes Zombie Necro Dragon, and Archfiend Zombie-Skull are also either Rare or Normal only. Avendread Savior is not exactly mandatory, but it would also be nice to have as a Link 2 for Zombie decks. So yeah, a pretty straightforward list this time and not much crazy or spicy techs. Just an almost free deck to play, I'd say that you can mess around and have fun with.

deck_excerpt: Domain Monarch
deck_description: The main strategy of the deck is to have  Majesty's Fiend , March of the Monarchs and Domain on the field.  The other powerful monsters and spell/traps like Erebus, Ehther, Kuraz ,Stormforth and Escalation are for controlling the field. Kuraz is also a great draw power.  The draw power's of the deck are : Pantheism (one of the best searchers also), Kuraz and Reload .  And the last but not least are the searchers : Tenacity, Return (pop it with Kuraz for + 2), Pantheism and Goods (when you send pantheism)  This build doesn't play playset Edea and Eidos (they can be easily negated), Anchamoufrite can be very problematic with your strategy, because he can be stucked in Extra and that will nullify your Domain. Proof of Pruflas also can prevent your Ehther to resolve her effect. Your best solutions to play in their places are : 3x Vishuda (synergy with Prime Monarch) or 3x Linkslayer (Twin Twisters on legs). For tribute fathers my scheme is : 1x Edea, 1x Eidos, 3x Mithra , 3x Linkslayer and of course 1x The Prime Monarch. I find it as perfectly balanced.  Foolish Burial is mostly for Erebus and Edea. Erebus is for the Monster Reincarnation effect and Edea is for Monarch spell/trap recovery.

deck_excerpt: A fun and nostalgic deck that works.

deck_excerpt: "Yes, Let's put Thunder Dragon Colossus at 1. Nothing will go wrong, right?"               -Ronald Reagan probably
deck_description: Well, Thunder Dragon Colossus is limited on the banlist, so Thunder Dragons suddenly became more than just a rogue strategy.  Anyways, this is a Thunder Dragon Chaos deck. We're playing to turbo out Colossus and hopefully Titan on your first turn of play (which is surprisingly easy!)  Our Thunder Dragon lineup is 3 of the OG, 3 Dragondark, 3 Dragonmatrix, 2 Dragon Fusion, 2 Dragonroar, 1 Dragonhawk, and 1 Dragonduo. The newest Main Deck Thunder Dragons gain bonus effects when banished or sent from the field to the graveyard, like special summon a TD monster from the deck, tutor for a TD card (not monster, any card. Hooray for TD Fusion tutor!), getting another copy of the same card, etc. This is why we're also running a small Chaos package!  Our Chaos lineup is pretty brief; 3 Chaos Space, 1 Chaos Creator, 1 Wyverburster, 1 Collapserpent, and the Dragonduo from the TD lineup. We run these to banish TD monsters for value, and in the case with Dragonduo and Chaos Creator being Thunder-type monsters that are special summons from banishing, we can tribute them to cheat Colossus from the Extra Deck.  We include 2 monsters that aren't a part of these packages, but they banish so they're damn good. Batteryman Solar is a Thunder monster that allows you to banish a Thunder monster from the deck, and Aloof Lupine serves the same purpose as long as we banish a Thunder monster from our hand. Cheating TD monster effects from straight from the Main Deck is pretty bonkers.  I included 3 different Hand Traps into the deck; 3 Effect Veiler, 3 Maxx "C" and 2 Called by the Grave. These can honestly be anything. Just prepare for what you're primarily playing against to tech against that matchup. Drytrons? Droll and Lock Bird fucks with their turn massively.  Our spell lineup now, excluding ones previously mentioned. 1 Feather Duster, 1 Gold Sarc, 1 Instant Fusion, and 3 Allure of Darkness. Feather Duster ruins backrow decks like Eldlich, Generaider, and a good Monarch start. The Gold Sarc is an immediate effect activation for a TD monster of our choice, and the 3 Allure of Darkness is for draw power while fueling effects from our TD monsters with its banish clause.  Now the spicy shit: the Extra Deck! Most of the Extra Deck is generic and you can swap most of it out with your personal preferences.  We got 1 Colossus, 3 Titan, 1 Kaminari Attack, 1 Abyss Dweller, 1 Summer Summoner, 1 Masquerena, 1 Verte, 1 Phoenix, 1 Unicorn, 1 Apollousa, and 1 Accesscode.  Trust me when I say that all you really need in your extra deck is the Colossus, Kaminari Attack, and 2 Titans and not 3. Colossus, if you didn't know, floodgates ONLY your opponent from not being allowed to search cards from their deck. Note that they can still DRAW cards and send cards to the graveyard. Kaminari Attack is our Instant Fusion target, being a Thunder Fusion monster allows it to be tributed for either Colossus and Titan. Titan has a quick effect pop when a Thunder monster activates their effect from your hand. Please note that on nowhere on that card mentions "Once per turn". Oh yeah, and they have protection from destruction. With Colossus, you gotta banish a Thunder monster (More effects? Hell yeah!) and Titan allows you to banish and 2 cards from your graveyard, doesn't have to be just a Thunder monster.  And that's Thunder Dragons for ya! Have fun summoning Colossus and Titan turn 1 and your opponent not being able to do anything!

deck_description: If u want u can replace: 1 ghost ogre for third copy of ash blossom 3 droplet with 3 spell/trap removal or board breaker in side deck  What i side when i play match? i side 1-3 impermanence, 1 fusion destiny, 1-2 monster hand traps (if u going second u can side 1 maximus or 1 ecclesia), deppends  Using pot of prosperity: Banish 3 cards if u have in hand already both Aleister + Dogmatika/Destiny fusion Banish 6 cards if u don't have any of these or if u have only Aleister or only Dogmatika/Destiny fusion. Targets for banishing (most of the time): 1 mechaba, purgatrio, augoeidis, predaplant verde, framelord omega, Construct, fossil warrior.  Some of u will wondering why i play 2 ash and 2 droll, the reason is simple, i love these cards and i know they are the best hand traps in the current meta but if i have 2 ash in hand then one becomes brick and can't be used the same turn, same goes for droll, hand traps that can be used once per turn i playing x2 in main and if is devastating against some decks i have the third copy in side.  The side deck is build for the current meta, i didn't put any spell/trap removals, however, going first solemn judgment can respond. If u want u can replace droplet with lightning storm or spell/trap removal or board breaker.  in the main is 12 hand traps, 85% chance to open going first and 92% going second, if u want to change something feel free to do it but make sure to have at least 7-8 monster hand traps that can be appropiate targets for Small World and are compatible for almiraj (because of Maximus combo). The players which want 3 ash blosom feel free to do it but don't remove ghost ogre, u need at least 1.  SMALL WORLD: How small world works in this deck? Some of u maybe never played this card so i will explain. Banish 1 monster from your hand. To add Aleister in hand: reveal from the deck 1 of these: Ash, Veiller, Maximus, Droll, Ghost ogre To add dogmatika in hand: reveal from the deck 1 of these: Ghost ogre, droll, Aleister  About Maximus: Everyone using 1 copy of maximus (me also in the past) but that's wrong, Maximus x3 is the best. Normal summon whatever monster (even hand trap), summon almiraj - gardna - sp summon maximus - send in gy apcalone and ash dragon - set schism for winda - sp summon ecclesia in EP by ash dragon and add fleur in your hand. I mention that combo because the most of the people thinks Maximus is brick or bad draw, but is not. It's both starter and extender.  BUDGET VERSION: Remove 3 pot of prosperity. This is very strong card, going first it can give u access in total of 11 cards in 40 card deck, i consider pot of prosperity both starter and card for consistency, u can't replace it with upstart goblin or pot of desire, absurd, no chance. Add 1-3 mystic mine in the place of pot of prosperity, the reason is simple, if u don't have starter in your hand u can lock and stop your opponent from playing until u draw meltdown, u have 4 meltdown in main so u will be fine, this is your best option if u don't play pot of prosperity in this deck. Remove Droplet also. I don't recommend removing the destiny fusion package because if aleister and dogmatika is negated then u can summon predaplant verte and summon enforcer, basically after 2 negates u still can play, so really i don't recommend removing it, if u want u can replace it with dragoon package, 1 fusion, 1 dark magician and 1 red eyes... total of 3 cards, still is 100 dolars but enforcer or dragoon is worth it, u can target impermanence for replacement, this will save u the money for enforcer or dragoon. if u choice the dragoon package and u have 1-2 card free space, u can add Angel Statue - Azurune, it's good and is combaining well with all your engines.

deck_excerpt: A piece of yugioh history
deck_description: Gemini HERO, also known as Skill Drain HERO, HERO Beatdown, or HERO Beats, is a deck from the 2012 format. This deck was a versatile Anti-Meta Beatdown deck, which is described as a Beatdown deck that utilizes different control tools. This deck utilized the monster Elemental HERO Neos Alius in tandem with the card Gemini Spark to act as removal. Combining these with the card Skill Drain, allowed you to play a slower Beatdown strategy by stopping all monster effects on the field. This deck didn't utilize many monster card effects to ensure its win, so it could get away with and play around a floodgate like Skill Drain.  Neos Alius is your primary monster to beat down the opponent with, its 1900 ATK body was very capable of punching over most normal summoned monsters, while this together with Gemini Spark can help clear the opponent's board, the other important factor is that it's an Elemental HERO, meaning that it was capable of being used as fusion material for a generic line of Elemental HERO fusion monsters. With Miracle Fusion, you can use monsters on your field and/or in your grave yard as material for a fusion summon of an Elemental HERO fusion monster.  The Extra Deck acts sort of as a tool box, allowing you to get out monsters that you need for certain situations. In most cases, the deck would use Neos Alius with either Penguin Soldier or Snowman Eater to make Elemental HERO Absolute Zero. Absolute Zero while on top of having a fairly decent ATK of 2500, it also has an effect that destroys all of your opponent's monsters when removed from the field. Because Absolute Zero's effect activates after it leaves the field, it will still work even with Skill Drain active on the field, because Absolute Zero is no longer on the field, it is no longer negated by Skill Drain. Elemental HERO The Shining is a really good card to beat over larger monsters on your opponent's field. By using the Miracle Fusion to summon it, you will have banished at least 1 Elemental HERO monster, so it at the least be summoned out with 2900 ATK. On top of this, it also has an effect when sent from the field to the grave yard that lets you add up to 2 banished Elemental HEROs to your hand, allowing you to recycle the material used to summon it. Elemental HERO Great Tornado is a fairly strong monster, halving the ATK and DEF of all face-up monsters your opponent controls, on top of having 2800 ATK points, it was able to punch over practically any monster. Elemental HERO Nova Master is a decent card, having 2600 ATK on top of also letting you draw a card when it destroyed a monster is a good recovery option for the deck, being able to be made from the Wind-Up Zenmaines and one of your Elemenal HEROs. Elemental HERO Gaia is just another option to go into to beat over large monsters, being able to siphon half the attack out of a monster lets you punch in for a considerable amount of damage. That's as far as it goes with the Elemental HERO line-up for the Extra Deck. The Elemental HERO fusions are essentially your primary tools to use to deal adequate damage and combat stronger monsters. On top of all of this as well, the deck utilizes Super Polymerization, so you're able to use your opponent's monsters to fuse as well, so it makes for a really good removal tool.  From here I'll go over certain key cards in the deck. Elemental HERO Stratos will either act as a tool to remove your opponent's Spells and Traps, or it can be used to search out your Neos Alius to play on the follow-up turn. Stratos on top of E - Emergency Call, as well as 1 Reinforcement of the Army, allows you to effectively play 7 copies of your Neos Alius, which helps keep the deck really consistent.  You Play Pot of Duality for this reason, your deck isn't going to be doing a lot of special summoning all the time. Pot of Duality lets you dig into your deck for your turn. Whether that be drawing a Gemini Spark, a Neos Alius, or even one of your Trap cards, Pot of Duality lets you get the cards that will get your strategy online.  Thunder King Rai-Oh stops the opponent from searching for cards in their deck, and it can also negate a single special summon. This is a pretty decent card to normal summon, as its 1900 ATK points can be hard to hit over in a good amount of circumstances.  Crusader of Endymion is played mostly because it's another Gemini monster with a comparable 1900 ATK points. It doesn't enable your fusions like Neos Alius, but it does give your more consistency in getting your Gemini Spark online.  Beast King Barbaros can be normal summoned, but its attack is changed to 1900, this card works well with Skill Drain, as Skill Drain with negate its effect, and it will return to its original 3000 ATK. This can be utilized in a couple ways. Either by using it as a big monster to clear the opponent's field, or to possibly have your opponent attack into it, and then activate the Skill Drain so Barbaros could potential destroy that monster.  As mentioned above, Gemini Spark acts as a control tool for the deck, allowing you to turn your Neos Alius and your Crusader of Endymion into removal options, and then Gemini Spark lets you draw a card. Combined with the card Hero Blast, Gemini Spark became much more powerful, allowing you tribute the Neos Alius to destroy a card on the field, and then Hero Blast would let you bring back the Neos Alius to your hand and destroy a monster on the field. This is a very power card combination that acts as the primary control tools for the deck, as it can easily remove valuable cards from your opponent's field.  I hope you enjoy this little piece of Yu-Gi-Oh!'s history. This deck is really fun, and I hope you guys will think so too.

deck_excerpt: M O N K I  F L I P
deck_description: Hi, Grayewick the Fusionist here, and due to the prevalence of Drytron, Lyrilusc, Tri-Brigade, and Zoodiacs in Master Duel, I cannot really fault people for committing bargains with the dark forces and returning to monke to get a fighting chance, and with that being said, presenting True Draco. A brief explanation of several choices, and the lack thereof other more common options. • x3 Amano-Iwato - This could either be Inspector Boarder, Kaiser Colosseum, Maxx "C", or anything else. I only chose this because I really want to resolve Card of Demise turn one. • x3 Solemn Judgment - You need protection against Harpie's Feather Duster and Lightning Storm. • "No Pot of Extravagance?" - If you value the +2 more than the 6 copies of Skill Drain, feel free to use it. I just don't because I don't have it yet and it conflicts with my current build. • "No There Can Be Only One?" - No, as well as Anti-Spell Fragrance, or Rivalry of Warlords. Often I find myself struggling to gain advantage just as much as my opponent due to it conflicting with my consistency pieces. You could play it if you wanna use Kaiser Colosseum as well, that'd be funny. No Chicken Game either, because I don't want to give my opponent more cards than they already have. I would've played Upstart Goblin, if I have three of it. Sky Strikers could also be funny with this if you really wanna be that guy. So yeah, it's True Draco. Nothing much else to say about it, but "monki flip".

deck_description:
Dinomorphia had Won almost every games against The Grinding Golden Lord, But in the New Format of Feb 2022, 3 Skill Drains are gonna be helping Eldlich for sure. Inspired by a tournament top deck and to prepare for the new format, this is a quite competitive version of the Cyber Dinosaur Cosplayers and Robots Legion. Some points:
  • Less NS, more Traps, more Responses to the opponent's actions. It's amazing that it actually works. Cause all we need is a Trap to start the game.
  • Gravedigger Trap Hole and Debunk are for things like Eldlich and Ash.
  • Ash was added for more interaction if having to go second first round and...
  • Ash tutors RexSturm into Psy End Punisher, is one of very few boss can get over Rex. So We addopted them.
  • 3 Ferret Flame. These are our Speciality. That can Handle even Those Psy End Punisher- aliked bosses. It makes Player shuffle their monsters into the deck. therefore Effect-immuned Monsters can do nothing but making a good fly.
  • 3 Brute. For Those who can attack directly, like the little Rank 1 birds. Also it's usually a plus 1 bringing back Theriza.
  • 2 Torrential Tribute. to Clear field. good against combo decks like @Ignister or Virtual World. Because our monsters all float.
  • Imprudent Intrusion.  testing this one. kind of a flexible card, it can kill 1 or bring back 1. base on the different of LP. it can bring back the big ones too.
  • I feel safer knowing there are 2 Alert in the deck.
  • Same with 2 Sonic and 1 Reversion. Totally Helpful to Dodge an Attack to the LP.

deck_description: This is Meteonis Draconids Beatdown with Skill Drain. Yes.   You can search for ANY trap using Drytron. Why? That's because this is one of the few deck that can use Beatrice AND Auroradon in the same turn. The quick explanation is that Beatrice would send a trap to the GY and Auroradon would add it to your hand. This strategy was way better when Imperial Order wasn't banned and Herald was alive, but it still is a respectable side among (usus) the many Drytron variants.   This deck can also search for Prisoner of Destiny and use it in the opponent turn (with masquerena) to negate a key card.     GLHF

deck_description: This deck is very simple and straight forward. The game-plan is to essentially draw your whole deck on one turn and win with Exodia. For newer or returning players, I'll lay out the function of the Numeron Engine.  Your Numeron engine includes the cards Numeron Wall, Numeron Network, Numeron Calling, and your Number Gate monsters. You want to use Numeron Wall to activate Numeron Network directly from the deck. You use the Numeron Network effect to activate Numeron Calling, which will summon your 4 Number Gate monsters from the Extra Deck. At this point, if you have Memories of Hope in your hand, you can use it to Draw 4 cards. Either way, you will then use the Number Gate monsters to make Saryuja Skull Dread and activate its effect to draw 4 cards.  Called By The Grave is necessary as it gives you protection from cards like Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring or Droll & Lock Bird which can stop your FTK Strategy.

deck_excerpt: "If I'm not using an extra deck, you shouldn't be using one either."
deck_description: Monarchs; an old archetype that has been in the game since 2004, focuses on tribute summoning for powerful effects that affect the board and hand of the opponent. Not too long ago, they got legacy support with more spell cards, trap cards, a field spell, and a new set of "Mega Monarchs": Level 8 Monarchs that can be tribute summoned using a tribute summoned monster to get an effect stronger than their predecessors.  Lets start with our Normal summons: 3 Edea the Heavenly Squire, 3 Eidos the Underworld Squire, and 2 Proof of Pruflas. Edea is a Level 1 monster that pulls another monster with 800 ATK and 1000 DEF from your deck. Eidos, is a Level 2 monster with 800 ATK/1000 DEF that allows you to immediately tribute summon a monster from hand when its summoned, doesn't matter if you normal or special summoned it. And then their Proof of Pruflas, a Level 3 special summon as long as you don't control a special summoned monster yourself. You can also immediately tribute summon a monster when its summoned, for an easy Monarch or Fiend!  Now our Tribute summons! These are the reason why we play the deck in the first place. We got 3 Erebus the Underworld Monarch, 3 Ehther the Heavenly Monarch, 1 Thestalos the Mega Monarch, 1 Kuraz the Light Monarch, and 2 Majesty's Fiend. Erebus and Ehther both send 2 Monarch Spell/Traps to activate their respective effects. Erebus sends any 1 card your opponent controls back into their deck. Can be from the field or GY. Ehther allows you to special summon a Monarch or Fiend from your deck, but you gotta return it to your hand in the end phase. Thestalos allows you to send a card from your opponent's hand to the GY, and you deal burn damage if the card sent was a monster and its based on its level. Kuraz pops up to any 2 cards on the field and then players draw 1 card for each card they control got popped by this effect. Note that Kuraz is one of the only Monarchs that can activate their effect on a special summon as well, but can't attack the turn its summoned. And then we got Majesty's Fiend, a Level 6 monster that can't be special summoned and prevents both players from activating their monsters' effects. It is without a doubt one of the best single tribute card you can throw in this deck. I previously had Vanity's Fiend in the deck, but Majesty's basically does the same thing.  Our spell and trap lineup now! These are what keeps the deck churning. We got 1 Foolish Burial, 1 Reinforcement of the Army, 1 One for One, 3 Tenacity of the Monarchs, 3 Pantheism of the Monarchs, 3 The Monarchs Stormforth, 3 Domain of the True Monarchs, 2 March of the Monarchs, 2 Return of the Monarchs, 1 Frost Blast of the Monarchs, and 2 The Prime Monarch. Foolish Burial, RotA, and One for One are obviously the generically good one-ofs that literally serve the purpose of either putting a Monarch or Monarch spell/trap into the GY for their GY effect or to Put Edei either on the field or into your hand, therefore starting your chain. Tenacity of the Monarchs is a Monarch spell/trap search as long as you have a Monarch in your hand to reveal. This card is a reason why we aren't running Terraforming for the field spell. Pantheism is a Pot of Greed as long as you have a Monarch spell/trap to discard and has a GY effect to reveal 3 Monarch spell/traps from your hand and your opponent selects one to add to your hand (Woo, another way to grab the field spell!) Monarchs Stormforth is a Quick-Play that allows you to tribute an opponent's monster for your Monarchs. Domain of the True Monarchs is our field spell and big payoff for playing the deck. It allows your Mega Monarchs (the Level 8 ones) to have their level lowered by 2, so they can be tribute summoned with a single monster! Anyways, the main effect we care about is if we are the only ones that control a tribute summoned monster and we don't have an extra deck, our opponent can't summon monsters from the extra deck. That is by far the strongest card in our deck that isn't Majesty's Fiend. March of the Monarchs prevents our tribute summoned monsters from being targeted and destroyed by card effects. Note that it doesn't mention Monarchs, it mentions tribute summoned monsters, so it gives protection to Majesty's as well! Return of the Monarchs is a search for a monster with 2400 ATK/1000 DEF or  2800 ATK/1000 DEF if you tribute summon a monster. Also note that Majesty's Fiend is 2400 ATK/1000 DEF so it can be searched with this card too! Frost Blast of the Monarchs is a pop for a set card on the field if we control any Monarch or Fiend, and has the GY effect to banish itself and another Monarch spell/trap to pop another set card. The Prime Monarch is a continuous trap that allows us to shuffle 2 Monarch spell/traps from the GY back into your deck and draw 1 card after. While its in the GY, you can banish another Monarch spell/trap to summon it as a Level 5 monster. More tribute fodder always helps the deck!  That's it for the deck honestly! You can put in any hand traps you might need or put in other Monarch spell/traps, like the one that allows you to tribute summon once during your opponent's turn. This deck is a little heavy on the SRs and URs, but it makes up for it by not needing to run an extra deck. Have fun not allowing your opponent to play turn 1!

deck_excerpt: Another Piece of Yu-Gi-Oh! History
deck_description: HAT, stands for Hand Artifact Traptrix. This deck was a wildly successful deck in the 2014 format and it dominated a lot of the top competition, so much so that the format would later come to be known as HAT Format. The deck, HAT, is broken down into 3 parts.  Hand, Fire Hand, and Ice Hand. Fire Hand is a 1600 ATK monster with an effect that allows you to destroy a face-up monster when its destroyed by your opponent's card, and then it lets you special summon an Ice Hand from the deck. Ice Hand's effect allows you to destroy a face-up Spell or Trap your opponent controls when it is destroyed by your opponent's card, and then it allows you to special summon a Fire Hand from the deck. The Hands in the deck allows the player to have a consistent way to break down the opponent's board, effectively punishing them for controlling a face-up monster on your turn. As neither of these effects have a once per turn restriction, you could use them over and over until you've wiped your opponent's field.  The next section is the Artifact lineup. The Artifacts are a series of monster cards that can be set in the Spell and Trap card zones, and they special summon themselves from the GraveYard when destroyed as well as apply an effect to give you additional advantage. In the case of HAT, the Artifacts that would be ran are Artifact Beagalltach, Artifact Moralltach, and the trap card, Artifact Sanctum. Artifact Beagalltach was used in the more combo oriented version of the deck, the control versions much like this one would just run the Moralltach and the Sanctums. Starting off with Artifact Moralltach, its effect allows you to summon it from your GraveYard when it is destroyed in your Spell and Trap card zone. If Moralltach was summoned on your opponent's turn, it allows you to destroy one face up card they control. Beagalltach's effect allows you to destroy a card in your Spell and Trap card zone when its summoned, this allows you to destroy your Moralltach and get it back as a monster to easily make the Rank 5 XYZ monster, Artifact Durendal. Artifact Sanctum's effect lets you summon an Artifact monster from your deck. Between the 3 copies of Artifact Sanctum, and the 3 copies of Artifact Moralltach, you are effectively playing 6 copies of Moralltach, which allowed the deck to maintain a lot of consistency.  Finally, the Traptrix. Traptrix are a series of cards that have different effects that revolve around the Hole trap cards, such as Trap Hole, Bottomless Trap Hole and so on. HAT would run 2 of the Traptrix, that being Traptrix Dionaea, and Traptrix Myrmeleo. Dionaea when normal summoned allows you to add a Hole trap card from your deck to your hand, but when it's special summoned, it allows you to destroy a Spell or Trap card your opponent controls. Myrmeleo when Normal Summoned allows you to Special Summon a Traptrix monster from the GraveYard in defense position, but when Myrmeleo is Special Summoned, it allows you to set a Hole trap card from your GraveYard, but it banishes it if it's still on the field during the end phase of your next turn. Traptrix monsters themselves are also unaffected by the effect of Hole trap cards, that makes them a pretty reliable Normal Summon, as they also have a decent amount of ATK points.

deck_excerpt: Yabba-Dabba-Doo!
deck_description:
Dinosaur was a popular deck of the 2020 format and still remains to be a fairly capable deck in Master Duel. The deck has a lot of power behind it that allows it to summon out monsters like Evolzar Dolkka and Ultimate Conductor Tyranno, two really powerful monsters that can help secure you games. With the monster Miscellaneousaurus, you can add protection to your dinosaurs that will let you safely make your plays and go into your big boss monsters. Miscellaneousaurus can also be used on your opponent's turn to act as protection from their destruction effects or negations on their turn to ensure your monsters have more staying power. There are a couple of different combo lines in the deck I will go over

Summon Souleating Oviraptor > Effect To Search > Search Miscellaneousaurus > Activate Miscellaneousaurus > Activate Miscellaneousaurus In The GY > Summon Animadorned Archosaur > Animadorned Archosaur Effect Destroy A Dinosaur > Add Double Evolution Pill. Optimally, you want to destroy either Babycerasaurus or Petiteranodon with the effect of Animadorned Archosaur so you can get an additional summon out of them. This is your primary Dinosaur combo line that can enable your plays into your Evolzar XYZ monsters, it can also allow you to summon Ultimate Conductor Tyranno. You also have your Scrap combo lines. Your Scrap combos can let you go into the Synchro monsters in the Extra Deck by using Scrap Raptor as the tuner material. Your average Scrap combo will look like this. Summon Scrap Raptor > Scrap Raptor Effect Activate > Destroy The Same Scrap Raptor > Add Scrap Chimera From Deck > Summon Scrap Chimera > Revive Scrap Raptor > Scrap Raptor + Scrap Chimera To Make Scrap Wyvern > Scrap Wyvern Revive Scrap Raptor > Scrap Wyvern Effect Destroy Scrap Raptor > Summon Scrap Raptor From Deck.

At this point the Scrap Wyvern's effect will resolve by destroying a card on the field. You have a couple options here depending on your established board. If you have a Babycerasaurus or a Petiteranodon you want to destroy those to get another dino on the field with their effect, if you control Lost World while your opponent has a token, you want to target the token for destruction, activate Lost World and then destroy either a Babycerasaurus or Petiteranodon from your deck for an additional dino summon. If you have neither of those, you can either decide to just destroy a card your opponent controls or you can destroy your own Scrap Wyvern and use it to equip to Borreload Savage Dragon to provide yourself two negations, additionally, if you decide to play a generic Rank 4 XYZ monster in the Extra Deck, you can use this line to get you into those fairly easily if Scrap Raptor is your only combo piece.

Summon Scrap Raptor > Scrap Raptor Effect Activate Destroy Itself > Add Scrap Chimera > Summon Scrap Chimera > Revive Scrap Raptor. At this point you have your two level 4 monsters you can turn into a Rank 4 XYZ. Keep in mind if you draw into the Scrap Chimera, you just want to use Scrap Raptor's effect to destroy itself on the field, and then this enables you to summon your Scrap Chimera from your hand, from that point you revive your Scrap Raptor from the Grave Yard. The field spell, Lost World puts a lot of the deck online. Here's a typical Lost World combo line Activate Lost World > Summon Souleating Oviraptor > Souleating Oviraptor Effect Add Miscellaneousaurus > Activate Miscellaneousaurus In Hand > Activate Souleating Oviraptor's Second Effect > Target The Token For Destruction > Activate Lost World > Destroy A Babycerasaurus or Petiteranodon From The Deck > Summon Dinosaur.

Outside of this, Lost World offers you protection and acts as a mild floodgate, as its effect will make it so the opponent can only target tokens with card effects. You have a couple different ways of activating the destruction replacement effect of Lost World such as the Scrap combo listed above. There's some parts of the deck I haven't really gone over, and I might possibly update this to include more information. I hope this description of this deck was helpful to newer/returning players, or anyone generally interested in this deck.

deck_excerpt: Get Your Game On!
deck_description:
HERO is a popular strategy introduced in the Yu-Gi-Oh! GX era. First introduced were the Elemental HEROs and the Destiny HEROs, and the anime later introduced the Evil HEROs. Later on, the manga introduced the Masked and Vision HEROs. HEROs have been played differently over the years in many different decks. This deck combines the power of all of the HEROs together for a very powerful OTK strategy. The modern HERO deck is a non-linear combo deck, that aims to One-Turn-Kill(OTK) the opponent fairly consistently, but it can also set up a couple different powerful floodgates to slow down your opponent.

Your main starters of the deck are your Elemental HERO Stratos, Vision HERO Faris and your Vision HERO Vyon. In most cases, Stratos will search you Faris, which will allow you to get into your Vision HERO Combo. Vyon will be the last card summoned on your Vision HERO combo but sometimes it will need to be utilized as a starter to dump a HERO into the deck like Shadowmist to get a search to get more of your combo pieces, or Malicious to go into Xtra HERO Cross Crusader in a pinch to get your combo pieces.

There are a couple different combo lines in the deck I will attempt to line out as best as possible.


Stratos + Any HERO


Stratos > Search Faris > Special Summon Faris > Put Increase In Spell/Trap Zone > Activate Increase Sending Faris To GY > Summon Increase > Summon Vyon > Vyon Effect Send Malicious To GY > Vyon Effect Banish A HERO Other Than Malicious to Add Polymerization. Summon Cross Crusader > Cross Crusader Effect Revive Malicious > Cross Crusader Effect #2 Send Malicious To GY And Search > Add Liquid Soldier To Hand Activate Polymerization > Use Stratos + Liquid Soldier To Make Elemental HERO Sunrise > Liquid Soldier Effect to Draw 2 on Chain Link 1 and Sunrise Effect to Add Miracle Fusion From Deck To Hand on Chain Link 2


 This is a common series of combos for the deck that you'll be able to do fairly consistently to put a lot of powerful monsters on the field, what you end on will be up to you, with Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer, you can also use your Cross Crusader to add Destiny HERO - Denier to your hand and then use the Denier + Malicious to make Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer with the Polymerization There are other combos you can do depending on the different pieces you have in your hand.

Fusion Destiny


Activate Fusion Destiny > Send Destiny HERO - Malicious + Destiny HERO - Denier > Summon Destiny HERO - Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer.
This line is very straight forward, it allows you to produce a Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer on your field while having 3 summons set up in your GY through Malicious and Denier. Fusion Destiny > Send Shadowmist + Malicious To Summon Destiny HERO - Dangerous > Shadowmist Effect > Search Stratos > Stratos Search Faris.
Using Fusion Destiny to make Destiny HERO - Dangerous like this allows you to get a search and summon from Shadowmist and Malicious respectively. You can use this to go into your Vision HERO combo as well as the Malicious in the GY puts the effect of Xtra HERO Cross Crusader online. You have a lot of options for what you can search off Shadowmist but if you're trying to start a combo you're going to want to search either a Faris or a Stratos depending on what other cards are in your hand. From the point that you add the Faris you can proceed to go into your Vision HERO combo. Keep in mind however that Fusion destiny locks you into Dark attribute HEROs for the reamainder of the turn.

I'll line out a use for the combo that allows you get still summon Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer even though you've used your Fusion Destiny. Faris Effect Discarding a HERO For Cost  > Faris Summon > Faris Effect > Place Vision HERO Increase in your Spell/Trap Zone > Increase Effect, Tribute Faris > Summon Increase > Increase Trigger Effect > Summon Vision HERO Vyon > Vision HERO Vyon Trigger Effect > Send Destiny HERO - Denier From Deck to GY > Vision HERO Vyon Ignition Effect > Banish Elemental HERO Shadowmist > Add Polymerization.

 This line allows you to put the Denier in your GY to summon it with Malicious, allowing you to make Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer using either your Denier + Malicious or your Denier + Dangerous. Alternatively to this, you could just use Dangerous's effect to send your Destiny HERO - Denier and then summon Malicious from your deck to make Cross Crusader out of Dangerous + Malicious, but in either case you want to use the Vision HERO combo to add the Polymerization to fuse into your Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer. The deck's optimum 1st turn board consists of summoning Destiny - HERO Plasma and Masked HERO Dark Law. These 2 cards together put a lot of pressure on the opponent because they are extremely powerful floodgates that will slow down their turn, or even outright stop their plays. Mask Change can be searched by Special Summoning Shadowmist, but keep in mind only 1 Shadowmist effect can activate per turn. Mask Change allows you to not only access your Dark Law, but it can also help the deck OTK, or even add a layer of protection for Stratos against targeting negation. You can use the Mask Change to help Stratos avoid being negated by effect negating cards that target such as Effect Veiler and Infinite Impermanence. When you summon the Stratos and activate its effect to search, if your opponent activates either Infinite Impermanence or Effect Veiler to target your Stratos and negate it, you can use the Mask Change to turn Stratos into Masked HERO Blast, and because Stratos left the field to summon Masked HERO Blast, the Effect Veiler or Infinite Impermanence would lose their target and you'll still be able to get your search with Stratos.


I've opted to play Super Polymerization in this deck in order to hit a lot of the bigger monsters the opponent will have out this format, such as playing Elemental HERO The Shining as a target to hit cards such as Swordsoul Grandmaster - Chixiao, Eldlich The Golden Lord or Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder. Elemental HERO Great Tornado allows you to hit cards such as Baronne de Fleur, Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess, Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon, Virtual World Kyubi - Shenshen or Barrier Statue of the Stormwinds. Outside of being able to summon it with Elemental HERO Liquid Soldier, you can also summon Elemental HERO Absolute Zero with Super Polymerization to hit cards such as Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying or Adamancipator Risen - Dragite. Elemental HERO Escuridao will mostly find use as being an extender summoned off the Miracle Fusion but with Super Polymerization you can use it to get rid of some cards like and opponent's Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer or Draco Berserker of the Tenyi. With a Destiny HERO monster you can Normal Summon, Super Poly also allows you to use your opponent's Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer to make your own Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer, this is really powerful as because their Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer wasn't destroyed, it doesn't get its effect to special summon. There's still some things in this deck I haven't went over. You'll have to play around with it to really get the feel of the non-linear stuff. I hope the description helps you figure out this very familiar strategy.

deck_excerpt: A list of an experimental build for Branded Beetroopers.
deck_description: Hi, Grayewick the Fusionist here, and I'm back with a TCG/OCG deck this time and one that is requested to me. Presenting, Branded Beetroopers. Before anything else, I just wanna say that this is not particularly a competitive version of the list, if anything I doubt the two of these decks could ever work harmoniously together (but that's a problem for another day, or list), so this will be more of a deck analysis and discussion regarding my thoughts upon testing it rather than just a regular deck profile, so don't expect anything short especially if you don't find reading particularly enjoyable. So the story behind this deck list is that an acquaintance of mine from Duelingbook sent me a message containing a link to a video of a Beetrooper gameplay (if you're here I appreciate the gift of thought), which shows a couple of lines that can set up to bring out Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon during your opponent's turn with a card for negation in hand with the help of Fusion Parasite, which I assume also means that it also allows you to bring out any Invoked Fusion monster as well provided that you have the correct materials on board. The philosophy behind the merging however is that the Beetrooper portion of the deck can easily bring out Dragoon no problem, but so can the Branded engine, so why not splash the two of them together? Chapter I: The Glaring Weaknesses. I play and test the Branded/Despia/Albaz strategy a LOT, since during the day it was released because one of my favorite Fusion Spells being the Fusion strategy enjoyer that I am is Super Polymerization, and Fallen of Albaz is just like a walking budget version of that, so I already have an idea on which cards to cut to make it as compact as possible without sacrificing consistency. But during the deck building process I have noticed that the Beetrooper portion of the deck requires a lot of main deck cards and one ofs in order to work ideally. Despite it only drawing soft bricks, you'd still want to draw the main starters. The main problem with this deck is that, the two engines clash with each other. The Branded portion of the deck xeno locks you into Fusion summoning only during that turn, else it cannot be activated, but the Beetroopers require Link summoning in order to start their turn, while the Beetrooper portion of the deck also xeno locks you into only summoning Insect monsters one way or another. I believe that there could've been a line somewhere that could make this relationship possible if one just wasn't as adamant as the other but, the only real way to somehow make it work is to force it. You gotta choose which one to pick as your main set up going first and your follow up going second. Ideally you'd want to start with the Branded portion of the deck first since it's the lesser restrictive of the two, but since we're playing a smaller package, it has to rely strongly on the luck of the draw. Chapter II: Sometimes coincidental synergies just ain't enough. Often times in your life you will find yourself on certain days stumbling upon things that you'll likely tell yourself that they could possibly fit together perfectly because of how much similarities they have. But things don't just match because of how much alike they are, it could also be because of how they're still able to find common ground despite how different they are to each other, but on the case of the latter, the risks of failing will be much higher. From what I've seen in testing pretty much just half of what the actual Beetroopers can do, I do admit that I am a beginner at piloting the deck since this day is literally the first day I have ever touched this archetype but I do also believe that this deck has a strong potential to grind. In testing, it even reminded me of the EARTH Machines, based on how much they Link climb, send to the GY, banish resources to extend, and recycle after setting up. And from what I already know about Branded Albaz is that it can DEFINITELY grind games without sacrificing board presence, that's why it's the best deck here in the OCG despite the plague of Maxx "C" and the Adventurer Token. But apart from the glaring weaknesses of this relationship that I have already discussed, there's more. Branded Albaz needs as much coverage as they can get, and merging it with a strategy that needs their Extra Deck as well for starters means that I would have to sacrifice some of those coverage. Beetroopers also face the same problem, because despite having been able to recycle their resources for the next turn, it really doesn't have any much guaranteed follow up anyway. And with these two problems in mind, you'd have to choose a path: It's either the Beetroopers or the Branded Albaz, one has to be the smaller engine and the other should do the grinding. Chapter III: No man can serve two masters. We've already discussed their differences, and what makes their relationship tough, but we still haven't discussed what brought them together in the first place: Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon. You see, this was a bit of an oversight on my part, I should've seen this problem coming. Sure, there are multiple ways of accessing it in this deck but the problem is, you've already got a tight enough Extra Deck space for one, what more for a more? So basically, both Beetroopers and Branded Albaz to an extent is clashing against each other again but this time on which one should bring Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon out. Branded Albaz can do it no problem with absolute ease, the only issue is that it's much more vulnerable to interruptions since it only plays a small amount of Branded cards in the main. Beetroopers can also do it somewhat decently, but a lot of things has to go right, and after that, it has already served its purpose. So yeah, that's pretty much everything that I have for the deck so far. I'm gonna be honest, I think these two are much better off without each other, considering how much they conflict and restrict one another from working as optimally as possible. It's sad but, maybe in another life where archetypes aren't as xeno locked as it is anymore they could work, but not in this one. Later.

deck_excerpt: Drytron post January 2022 banlist Alpha + zeta = dagda/scythe + F0 Utopic Draco Future + Apollousa / Draconids + Bethor
deck_description:
Drytron Megalith Combo deck Febraury 2022 This deck focuses on re-inventing the alpha + zeta combo bringing out new strategies. The Megalith component plays a huge role on the strat, with Phul actually recycling Benten from the grave and allowing rank 4 xyz plays. This deck doesn't include Diviner of the Herald, which could be seen as an insane choice, but since we do not put our focus on synchro summons but powerful xyz instead Diviner isn't needed. We use Manju (searchable with Benten) instead of Diviner for our normal summon, that can add from the deck whatever is needed for the combo to continue (Manju is used most of the times to access your Megalith engine). The rank 4 xyz (Manju + Ophiel) will often be tornado dragon to force the scythe lock or can be a Dweller (really impactful against certain decks). The 2 Mu Beta are mandatory, we abuse both for the full combo. The deck suffers from heavy backrow decks, I suggest playing Twin Twister, Feather, Cosmic and even Quadrantids in side deck. Deck features (in my humble opinion)
  • Cost: 7/10, since we are not playing Diviner, the deck results less expensive (but still relies on the expensive card F0 Utopic Draco Future)
  • Consistency: 8/10, we are playing a lot of generic cards that can lead us to the main combo
  • Competitivity: 8/10, the deck can outplay and compete against a lot of decks in the meta. The full combo is still insanely strong.
  • Fun: 9/10, this deck, compared to the old herald version, is much more fun and lead to multiple options in terms of combos.
Full board
  • 1 Alpha + zeta = dagda/scythe (extra deck lock) + F0 Utopic Draco Future (monster negate + steal) + Apollousa  (3 monster negates)
  • 2 Alpha + zeta = dagda/scythe (extra deck lock) + F0 Utopic Draco Future (monster negate + steal)+ Drytron Meteonis Draconids (huge untargetable beater, quick effect send 2 monsters to the gy)
Before going into Apollousa, it's possible to also go into Bethor (4+ card destroy, possibly a board wipe :D) Another super cool combo is dagda + i:p, you lock the opponent's extra, summon scythe and then link for apollousa (or unicorn/phoenix/borrelsword if you want to play it)! If you plan to propose this deck or get ideas from it I would appreciate the credits! Thank you for reading, I'm open to every kind of suggestion to improve the deck and its strat. I personally think this is a great way to bring on our lovely Drytron deck!

deck_excerpt: Rushe thunder lv10, protec thunder lv10, attac with thunder lv10.
deck_description: The Basic Idea is to rush out armed dragon thunder lvl10 as quickly as possible and keep it alive. So most of the cards in the deck are about either searching for armed dragon cards to start the combo chain, add more cards to your hand in order to utilize his effect, or protect armed dragon from destruction.  Outside of starting with thunder lv3 in your hand, you have a few ways to get the combo started.  Both Tempest and wind channeler will search for lv 3 at a discard cost to help you get started, but be warned that discarding a armed dragon thunder with channeler will NOT activate their graveyard effects as she's not a dragon. However, pairing it with tempest WILL activate their effects which means more searches on top of the search.  Armed Dragon flash will also make this work, as it SS's lvl 3 thunder from the deck. Thus helping you start the level up combo.  Artillery Catapult Turtle is also very useful. By tributing itself for its effect, you can rush out a thunder lvl 5, starting you in the combo from their instead of lvl 3.     Armed Dragon Lightning is likely to be your prime protection tool, as its searchable with thunder lv7's effect and recyclable with thunderbolt. If you can draw it, the field spell will basically make your thunder lv 10 and white unbeatable while it is in play, as it negates targets and destroys on your lvl 10 monsters.     Now the original Lv10 is here due to armed dragon blitz, as thunder's name becomes the same as the original, blitz can be used to SS the original lv10 at no cost. Which leads you to a top row nuke at the cost of a discard.     If you cannot get into thunder lvl 10 for some reason, you have other options. White is a great option as it can be SS'd if you managed to get decently far into the thunder combo but was stopped or if thunder is destroyed. Since it is paired with white veil, you get a backrow nuke and top row destroy on attack, and it negates any back row effects while it attacks which is great. While tempest is here mostly to push along the armed dragon engine and even reset it if needed, it can be used as a reliable attacker in a bind , as you special summon it by banishing armed dragons, even from the grave.  Now I have not put my extra deck largely for master duel reasons. as the star of your show is your main deck, you dont NEED specific extra deck cards in your extra deck to make this deck work. The extra deck just needs to be filled to be used for pot of extravagance. However, if you want to build your extra deck specifically for this deck. rank 10 xyz monsters will be your best bet, as that will be on your field the most with thunder lvl 10, normal lvl 10, and white. i personally recommend looking at the superdreadnought cards for this, but as every one is UR in master duel, they can get quite expensive. other possibilities are rank 7 xyz monsters due to tempest, you could stop at thunder lv 7 to put one of those out, aside from that im not sure what situation you'd use any others aside from link monsters.

Well you're in luck!  This deck is made up of only Normal and Rare trap cards and actually can put up a decent fight if you know when to activate cards.  Your main goal is to get some paleozoics on the field, Pacifics into the field zone to get some tokens on the board, phantasm spiral wave attached to a paleozoic or a token, and keep your opponent held down by the trap effects of each paleozoic, the hand effects of the phantasm trap cards, or lost wind as a card.  The extra deck can be something to go into if you have the proper cards on the field, like going into number 96/catshark and socuteboss and wipe the board or some cross-sheep combo, but your main combo will mostly wrap around your main deck. So good luck and have fun!

deck_excerpt: Play Gren Maju and use tokens to summon Zeroboros and clear the field when needed
deck_description:
This is a Master Duel optimization of my TCG Gren Maju Goats deck. The usual Gren Maju players are here with some token generators. Ash Blossom and Lighting Storm/Harpie's are interchangeable with other hand traps/techs or even another Left Arm Offering.

The objective as always is to banish cards and get out Gren Maju - The tokens can be used to link into Zeroboros with either a 1 star + Skyblaster or a flipped Scapeghost. Use Book of Taiyou to get your tokens same turn. Left Arm helps search Taiyou, or another spell if you don't have Scapeghost in hand. Plenty of Allure of Darkness targets, ideally you're banishing Necroface.

Knightmare into Zeroboros with the tokens. If you used Scapeghost, you'll be left with one sheep token - use this to have Linkuriboh trigger Zeroboros' banish effect once your opponent has a full board without negates. Win next turn if you're lucky. Just remember Zeroboros' is NOT a quick effect - it resolves AFTER the current chain.

deck_excerpt: Just a fun plant build for Master Duel Players that want to try something fresh. Enjoy the 6 more weeks of winter with this deck!
deck_description: Welp, this is my first post, more than likely not my last. Someone told me about Rikka and I immediately fell in love with the artwork and theme and pretty much cooked up this list immediately, in no way should this list be considered a final build. I noticed Rikka by themselves orient more towards control, but you can definitely turn them into a monster combo deck that can set you up insane board presence to wipe out your opponent or hold the line with their tribute effects. Also there's plenty of room with their typing, being water AND plants opens up insane options, I wanted to lay more into the plant side of things but there's plenty of water support to be considered as well. I had a ton of fun brewing with these cards and I plan on crafting this deck on Master Duel to see how it fares against the world! This one's for Horohoro and his endless field of butterbur! ... Or Something. Anyways, here's the list.  1x Tytannial, Princess of Camelias: One of the star techs of the deck, I'm a huge fan of the Plant Princesses and even though they aren't in archetype, all of them being Level 8 Plants allows them to synergize well with the main cast with relative ease. Tytannial works as a target negate, and is based after one of my favorite flowers. you can replace this with other cards like any of the other Princesses we don't run or something else like Mardel, Generaider Boss of Light.  1x Talaya, Princess of Cherry Blossoms: My other Princess tech and my favorite of the 4. Provides extra effect destruction protection which I always like to have more of, but feel free to experiment with other options.  1x Hellebore the Rikka Fairy: even though she's my personal favorite main deck monster, multiples will feel cloggy and we already run Camelia anyway. It is nice that she summons herself back for a tribute, I just wish it was a quick effect. You COULD get away with not running her, but just imagine how sad she'd be if you didn't use her at all. :'(  1x Snowdrop the Rikka Fairy: Extends and sets up your xyz plays, you could run more than 1 but it's not entirely necessary.  1x Erica the Rikka Fairy: Rikkas have a battle handtrap! That summons itself back! How cool is that?!  1x Mudan the Rikka Fairy: Adds a Rikka spell or trap to hand when you summon her, probably why she doesn't float back?  3x Cyclamen the Rikka Fairy: Tributes itself to reduce 2 levels, also brings itself back. you could replace this with another water level 4 to make Bahamut Shark but I decided to stick in house for theme-based fun.  3x Primula the Rikka Fairy: Summons itself from hand when another card gets tributed, also increases the levels of your plants by 2, this with evil thorn or lonefire is insane and she's really useful for facilitating other combos as well. arguably the most important Rikka card mechanically so definitely run her at 3  1x Rose Girl: Recyclable Halq target, level 3 for access to level 7 synchro plays.  3x Lonefire Blossom: The ultimate enabler for plants. tributes itself to summon ANY plant from the deck.  1x Ash Blossom and Joyous Spring: feels necessary but not in multiples since Called by hits Maxx C.  1x Spore: Same as Rose Girl but you can make Queen of Thorns with it. also an excellent One for One target.  3x Evil Thorn: Does petty burn damage and pulls 2 from deck making it a free Jasmine most of the time. this is what you;re aiming for with Lonefire and one for one if you don't get a copy in hand.  1x Copy plant: Extra Halq target but can realistically be anything. Go nuts.  1x Rikka Petal: Wittle beebee Rikka! Searches for a Rikka monster and summons itself if you only control plants, not terrible, basically a plant Treeborn Frog.  1x Rikka Flurries: Oh how fickle can they be, amirite? *shot* Forces your opponent to tribute a monster if you tribute a rikka but if you decide to go further into the extra deck it'll destroy itself at the end of your opponent's turn, definitely think before dropping this card, another spell could be reduced for this but I wouldn't try to rely on this one as amazing as the artwork is.  1x Harpies Feather Duster: Wipe up that backrow hate, skill drain is at 3 and vanity's is legal in Master Duel so we definitely want to keep the opponent's reverse cards in check.  1x One for One: One card in hand for a level 1, very fair trade considering 1 level 1 = huge profit. EZ math.  1x Monster Reborn: clutch extender or can revive a Princess  1x Pot of Avarice:Shuffe 5 monsters in grave to the deck or extra to draw 2. Recursion and draw, why be Extravagant?  3x Rikka Glamour: Searches a Rikka and lets you tribute to search any plant. It's really in here more for the second effect than the first to get out a Princess.  2x Called By the Grave: My favorite quick play spell currently since it checks so many things by removing a monster in grave from play AND negating that card's effects. Eldlich and Striker hate this card along with every handtrap amongst other things.  2x Enemy Controller (?!): this can be anything, I just figured it'd be fun to steal my opponents' things mid combo. a better card might be trade-in, ice dragons prison, imperm, but this is for the brave.  2x Twin Twisters: chainable hate for backrow hate.  2x Rikka Sheet: Catch your opponent's monster slippin' and negate its effects, or tribute a plant to make it slide on over to your side of the field for the turn and turn it into a plant.  1x Rikka Tranquility: Rikkursion (see what I did there?). If you tribute a plant you can get another one with the Rikka you summon off this, meaning you can spot dodge amongst other things.     EXTRA DECK  1x Borrelload Savage Dragon: this can be anything else but since you'll probably send jasemine to make needlefiber why not turn it into 2 monster negates?  1x Perrialis, Empress of Blossoms: Can net you a princess or more fuel to tribute  1x Queen of Thorns: Burn your opponent for playing the game. I might switch Tytannial to Marina to protect this because it makes the other player stop to think for a second, 1000 LP is a lot  1x T. G. Wonder Magician : can be any other tuner synchro, it's just nice to be able to pop things.  1x Sacred Beast Hyperyton: Can detech an xyz to negate a card as the same one attached and can attach something from grave every turn, even more reason to try ouy Marina Princess of sunflowers. We make this by tributing Strenna with an xyz material  1x Teardrop the Rikka Queen: That art. <3 That aside her effect to target and tribute anything on either player's turn is amazing. might drop the bahamut shark gimmick for another one of her and Strenna  1x Kanzashi the Rikka Queen; turns herself into a literal monster reborn if something gets tributed, also protects your board further which is nice  1x Bahamut Shark: makes Toad. that's it.  1x Bagooska the Terribly Tired Taper: make everything take a nap in an emergency.  1x Rikka Queen Strenna: lets you pick up a Rikka monster in grave and if she's tributed makes a bigger xyz with her as material. Hyperyton is her best buddy  1x Toadally Awesome: Shark makes this. this negates things. that's kind of it.  1x Hope harbinger Titanic Galaxy: Negates spells and forces your opponent to target it for attacks. If only he was a plant.  1x Aromaseraphy Jasmine: the link we aim for. lets you tribute a plant for any plant like lonefire.  1x Crystron Halqufibrax: Sets up synchro plays, also summons Wonder magician in emergencies'  1x Saryuja Skull Dread: this can be any link 4 but I have this one, also the 4 monster effect can come in handy in a bind.        ...and that's it! all you really need to know to get started is Evil thorn is your way into jasmine  and just pay attention to what you may need. Happy Dueling!

deck_excerpt: High expectations bundled with grief, agony, and disappointment
deck_description: New video uploaded. Link below ( youtube.com/watch?v=7HcvyKi8_Jo&feature=y )   The adverse side effects of high expectation includes depression, agony, and something to do with being slightly bipolar (not to say I am or not). Three years after getting new support for this archetype, the adverse technicality still holds up; but with cards like Nibiru, Forbidden Droplet/Chalice, and infinite impermanence being staples, the deck would struggle more than ever. Luckily there is a market to improve this, and hundreds of people would pull stupid shit for fifteen seconds of fame. That being said this is the post mortem of Magical Musketeers. In reality, the deck wasn't too hard to make nor play by my own virtue. Rather than trying solely to focus on making the deck as pure as a prostitute on a Sunday, I insist to find some strengths and weakness to make use of a card known as "Crossout Designator". So by adding cards like Nibiru, Ash Blossom, Imperm, and Forbidden Droplet this would allow the deck to somewhat dodge these as due to negations from some of these most played cards are their weaknesses. Another factor of their issues is the lack of OTK preparations to which "Magical Musket - Crooked Crown" and "Borrelsword Dragon" has done a good job in doing so. Finally comes card recovery in all forms, which wasn't too big of a deal to solve so I used "Pot of Avarice", "Daigusto Emeral", and "Magical Musketeer - Wild" to allow the recoveries to be slightly easier. Also included was the Phoenix Enforcer package, which has become a staple of sorts with just about everyone these past few months.

deck_excerpt: Use some deck manipulation with slash draw to one-shot your opponent for the otk.
deck_description: Disclaimer: this is an ocg deck and could never exist in the tcg due to slash draw being limited to 1.  Use some deck manipulation with slash draw to one-shot your opponent for the otk. This deck has a ton of card draw and can FTK but I won't label it as an "FTK" because that would be misleading.  Here is the combo: Use top share and place slash draw on top of your deck, set Big Eye, Use book of Taiyou to flip Big eye face up, place slash draw on the space that would be active (I can't describe it so read the card and how it works), set every card in your hand that you can (leave 1 spell/trap space open), and finally activate slash draw for a ton of damage.  The combo can also be done in other ways like just going for the big eye and hoping for a slash draw since it's just a great way to set up the cards that you draw next if you whiff.  This deck is built very similarly to an exodia deck but requires less specific cards in hand for the combo.

deck_excerpt: I've been Sunseed-pilled.
deck_description: The whole deck revolves on link summoning the Sunavalon Dryas using Sunseed Genius Locci to the search Sunvine Sowing, activating it to summon Sunseed Twin. Now as CL1 you revive the Genius Locci with Twin's effect and CL2 you'll use Dryas' effect to gain life points (since you took effect damage from Sowing) and summon Sunvine Healer. Remember to use Healer's effect to gain life points by targeting Dryas. Now you use Dryas and any other monster to go into your first Aromaseraphy Jasmine, but remember to leave one monster in a zone she points to. Now use Jasmine's effect to tribute a monster it points to and summon Aromage Laurel. Now link Laurel and the remaining monster in the main monster zone into your second Jasmine. This triggers Laurel's effect to gain life points, thus triggering the soft once per turn search effect of each Jasmine. From then on, it's up to you to decide which two plant monsters you need. I usually search for Snowdrop and Rose Girl to unbrick my hand with the former and have a monster to replace the one tributed for Snowdrop's effect with the latter.  NOTE: The side deck is not really a side deck and more of something to look at to remain humble while I was building this deck.
