deck_excerpt: Combining 2 trap archetypes created this literal war crime of a deck.
deck_description: Well, this might just be somehow the best and worst thing my wicked brain could create right now: Traptrix Eldlich. Traptrix is an archetype that build itself upon the normal "Hole" trap cards, cards that somehow negate and/or destroy monsters when they're summoned or their effects are used. We're mixing it with the splashable Eldlich archetype, which you should be very familiar with right now if you know ANYTHING about what's going on in YuGiOh right now, and if you don't, I recommend you read a few of their cards to see what kind of grind game they are capable of.  As stated, I combined 2 trap decks to make this abomination of a control deck, using cards like Void Trap Hole, Floodgate Trap Hole, and Network Trap Hole to keep your opponent off of their main starter monsters. Void's activation requirement is your opponent special summoning a monster with at least 2000 ATK. This can work if your opponent summons other monsters and with lower ATK values. You get to negate the effect of any of the summoned monsters with 2000+ ATK and pop it. Floodgate sets a summoned monster to face-down defense position and it can't change its battle positions by any means. Big thing to note with this Trap Hole: it works when your opponent summons multiple monsters and it'll set ALL of them face-down. That's nuts. Network banishes monsters special summoned from the main deck or GY face down, and Holes that banish are usually better than others, but the summon HAS to be from the main deck or GY. Gravedigger's negates the effect of a monster from the hand, GY, or banished zone, and burns them for 2000 damage if its successfully negated!  With all these "Hole" cards, we might as well run the Traptrix archetype, who's monsters are unaffected Hole traps. We have Myrmeleo, which will add a Hole trap to our hand if normal summoned and pop a spell/trap your opponent controls if special summoned. Dionaea reborns a Traptrix monster on its normal summon and sets a Hole from your GY but if its on the field at the end phase of your next turn, so it will most likely be used! Mantis adds a Traptrix monster on its normal summon and allows you to switch a set spell/trap from your field for one in hand once per turn as a quick effect. Vesiculo allows you to special summon it from hand if we send a set trap from our field to the GY, but Eldlich does this and he's bigger, so you'll do this for one of your Link or Xyz monsters most likely.  We got Eldlich the Golden Lord, the ultimate grind monster that allows you to send a spell/trap you control to the GY to summon him and with protection and a stat boost if summoned with his effect. If we have Eldlich, we might as well run the archetype cards to summon and support him. We have Eldlixer of Scarlet Sanguine which will summon Eldlich from the deck of GY, which is good enough to be ran. Our only 2 spells are 2 copies of Cursed Eldland, which can allow you to pay 800 to search Eldlich or a Golden Land trap from our deck. Note that only zombie-type monsters can attack if you activate this effect. Oh yeah, and if its sent from the field to the GY, you can foolish an Eldlich or Golden Land card. Now we have Huaquero of the Golden Land and Conquistador of the Golden Land. These are our only 2 Golden Land spell/traps and they get to act as trap monsters when activated and gain a bonus effect if Eldlich the Golden Lord is in your control. Huaquero banishes a card from either GY and Conquistador pops a face-up card on the field. They both have the effect to banish themselves from the GY in the end phase to set an Eldlixer from our deck to our field, and our only one is Scarlet Sanguine, so we'd get another Eldlich out anyway.  Now we'll go over our 2 non-archetype cards. Parallel eXceed can special summon itself from our hand if we link summoned, and to a zone it points to. If we manage to summon eXceed with its effect, we can pull a copy of it out of our deck. These eXceed are treated as Level 4, so we can use 'em for Link or Xyz plays, depends on the occassion. Skill Drain is for when we're more on the Eldlich plan than the Traptrix plan. Monster's effects are negated. So fun...  And now the Extra Deck, which you can splash anything in, but these are personal preferences. 2 Rafflesia allows you to send a Hole from deck to GY by removing a material to gain that hole's effect on a quick effect. It also gives your OTHER Traptrix monsters destruction protection from battle and card effects. Allomerus allows you to reborn a plant/insect monster from your GY by removing 2 materials and allows you to gain control of an opponent's monster that was sent to the GY or banished zone by one of your card effects at the cost of 1 material. Number 81 is just in case we have 2 Eldlich laying on the field, so we might as well get a slightly larger guy with protection from card effects. This is a monster you can honestly switch out for a GOOD Rank 4 Xyz like Abyss Dweller of Time Thief Redoer. Zeus is quite obvious why we run him: Make Xyz, use an effect of it, attack, summon big guy that has a quick effect board wipe. 3 Traptrix Sera, our Link 1 Traptrix allows us to special summon a unique Traptrix monster from deck if a normal trap card is activated. It doesn't even have to be a Hole trap or YOUR trap. Free special, woo! And vice-versa, it allows you to set a Hole if another Traptrix' effect is activated. 3 Cularia, and the main reason why I wanted to try Eldlich with this, is our Link 2 monster that allows us to set a Hole trap we just used back on the field instead of sending it to the GY and during your end phase, you get to reborn a Traptrix monster to defense position. The amount of possible recursion this single card provides is bonkers provided it sticks on the field, but its pretty good if you activate a Hole, set it, and use that set card to summon Eldlich. And lastly is our generic Link-climbing cards. Phoenix, Unicorn, Accesscode, and Apollousa, which has a quick effect negate once per chain as long as it has 800 ATK to sacrifice. Oh, and it gains 800 ATK for each of its materials, so you'll usually have 2-4 negates.  That's it for the deck list! Honestly, it seems solid, but you can definitely replace the 3 Skill Drain with a copy of Imperial Order since you only have 2 spell cards and 2 other cards that you prefer, but it DEFINITELY gets shit on with a Harpie's Feather Duster, Lightning Storm, and any monster that has protection from Trap cards. Hopefully y'all learned something from this. Have fun making your opponent wanna rip their own hair out by not allowing them to play the game!

deck_excerpt: The World Legacy's power is awakening. But will you be the choosen one ?
deck_description: Hy there...  Here is my decklist of a pure Mekk-knight deck. For the few people who never seen this archetype, this deck where released in 2018 and the gimmick of mekk-knight is to play with both player's collomn.  In fact, most of them have the effect that let you summon himself from hand as long as there is two cards on the same collomn on the field and you special summon the mekk-knight on this collomn, but you can only speciel summon one copy of each name per turn.  First of all, mekk-knight is meant to mostly goes second, because their sommun doesn't trigger negates, which is nice to break boards, on top of their high Atk and Def point, and their easy summon condition when going second, plus they are super consistent and fastly swarm the board with high stats monster.  This is the reason why I don't play any hand-trap on main except nibiru, because every hadtrap won't be effective 100% of the time while board breaker on going second will be pulled of more often. Plus, our format is mostly going first deck, so playing a going second deck gives an insane advatage because the result of the coin flip will basically never matter as you will go second 90% of the time. Plus, a nibiru on main can be super effective as some deck won't be expecting him on game one.  I play gameciel as a way to settup collomn for "blue sky" who can search from one to three mekk from your deck to your hand, and if this resolves, you will certainly otk your opponent.  Girsu is obviously a three of because it is a one-card iblee, which can setup your following up and your collomns easely. On top, I play corruptor Iblee because she will summon on the opponen't side of the field, so great for "blue sky" and enabe your opponen't for playing nibiru at all, and might shut down a lot of meta deck, mostly tri-brigade and swordsoul, who will struggles getting rid of her and not focuses on your board. But becareful of anaconda verte predaplant, you might end of giving them a free access to dragoon or DPE (or battle buttler for prank-kids).  This deck is really good and have a lot of good matchups against meta decks, one of the easiest one is Sky Striker, mostly thanks to your mekk-knights being able to swarm the field, and also some card are a huge counter to them, just like iblee, gameciel world legacy's whispers, a trap that negate spells on field that is on the same collomn of a mekk-knight (this is not a trigger effet and can even prevent any dodging).  To be honest, there is no budget option for pot of prosperity, this card is unfortunately mandatory, especially since pot of desire, the only card that where not bad enought to see a little bit played, but now, prosperity is a must-play.  I play gameciel because the bird lock isn't releavant anymore, since simogh got hit, and I don't see any deck running a barrier statue to normal nummon and pass... I would also recommand you to change the evenly matched for lightning storm if you can afford it, but I can't so I have to play some "budget" option instead, that doesn't really synergise with the deck and make you loose your deck advantage by making you loose your battle phase.  I know there is a lot of people who want to play "World Legacy World Armor" and "World Legacy succession", but I found out thatthe WLWA combo is like putting all your eggs on the same basket, and I prefer keeping more board presence to be able to control my opponent easier. Also, by playing the deck a lot, I've found out that succession is an amazing card but isn't needed on mekk-knight, because usually, you will rapidly win or rapidly loose, and I have never used this card. This is the reason why I play a one-of called by, who can prevent an ash on Blue or, more deadly, A droll and lock bird.  For the side deck, there is a lot of heavy backrow trategy, so I had to play tree of twin twister on top of the two cyclone to get rid of the skill drain and ice dragon's prison to banish the two Eldlich, which means game for us. Also, putting a contact "C" might proove fatal against sky striker or prank-kids and swordsoul and many other decks. Lancea is great because it make passes turn any flowandereese deck and handicaps phantom knight (in the condition that they haven't they adventurer negate). Red reboot is just another backrow-hate.  This deck might seems like nothing but from now, if you still play two cards on the same collomn, karma will send you a mekk-knight deck and you will learn why you have to NEVER play two cards on the same collomn.  A pretty fun deck with a lot of potential, each duel is for me like a boss fight, where I have to give everything I have to break the opponen't board and setup a little bit of control, who can prove fatal if they don't have enough cards to come bach.

deck_excerpt: x3 Gouki the Powerload Ogre under Skill Drain is comedy quintessential
deck_description: Hi, Grayewick the Fusionist here. Did you ever, at least once in your life, wished to be able to beat the everliving shit out of your opponent? Well, sadly we can't because that'd be classified as Assault but hey, I've got an alternative that can be just as good as that. Presenting, Powerload Ogre Turbo. Part I: The game plan. It's simple. Going 1st, you either make two Gouki the Powerload Ogres or one of it and a Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax protected with I:P Masquerena, or if you drew the nuts, two Gouki the Powerload Ogre AND a Masquerena protected Avramax. Going 2nd, you pray that you're able to draw either Lightning Storm or Evenly Matched and Gouki Suprex + another name and proceed as usual. No, we're not using Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Nights here because the bricks just aren't worth it, but we're using the Codebreaker package just because it's a generic Link climbing tool for Warrior decks. All gas, no brakes. The only reason why I run Lightning Storm in this build instead of Evenly Matched is because the only interaction we have with our opponent is the Battle Phase. Part II: The hand traps (I guess). The only hand trap you need here is Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, really. I only chose Droll & Lock Bird because fuck Drytrons, and I deliberately did not craft Maxx "C" out of spite to the OCG ban list, and the fact that MD is using that dog shit format is enough proof to me that Konami never learned from their mistakes in the past format but I digress. Basically this could be any staple you want. If you want to play Photon Thrasher as a starter as well, fuck it, it's a free Special Summon and a Warrior on board. Part III: The staples If you want to use a consistency card, either Upstart Goblin (though counterproductive to the game plan which is OTKing) or Pot of Prosperity (which is also kinda counterproductive since it halves the damage you deal during the turn you use it) could be nice. Pot of Extravagance is bad because you do not have control over which cards you're gonna banish, and there will be games where you need most if not all of your Extra Deck cards. The draw 3 from Card of Demise could be good, if not only because it just straight up defeats the purpose of your deck by not making you deal damage when it is used. You know what else is funny about this deck? Your Gouki the Powerload Ogres can comfortably sit under Skill Drain, so if you wanna run that as well, go for it. Overall, this deck doesn't really need to "have" the Masquerena + Avramax package, it's just an additional towers boss monster that I thought would be nice to have since it's not really that hard to make in this deck, so the only mandatory UR in this deck is the triple copies of Gouki Re-Match. It's a pretty straightforward Link climbing deck, it can be just as budget or expensive as you want depending on whether you wanna run Crossout Designator with at least 1 copy of Nibiru, the Primal Being as a target or not, it's totally up to you.

deck_excerpt: A budget build for a pure madolche deck
deck_description:
To start the combo chain, Special Summon Petingcessoeur or summon Magileine and search Petingcessoeur. Then Special Summon Puddingcess from Deck or Hand. Xyz Summon Glassoufle in Defense Position. Activate Glassoufle effect, sending Petingcessoeur to the GY and targeting anyone. Xyz Summon Puddingcess Chocolat-a-la-Mode using Glassoufle. Activate A-la-Mode effect to send Petingcessoeur back to the deck (if Chateau is on the field, don't put it in hand). A-la-Mode triggers and activate it detaching Glassoufle. From here we have a few options. If Anjelly wasn't used to find Petingcessoeur yet, it can be used to find the follow up cards. Otherwise, choose Hootcake with A-la-Mode effect and onto the field. Banish Glassoufle for Hootcake's effect and Special Summon Messengelato. With Messengelato we can find the 3 main spell cards in the Madolche archetype:
  • Salon: Any Madolche that returns from Field or GY to Hand or Deck allows to search a Madolche Spell/Trap and set it directly to the Field, therefore, it's another way to search the main Spell cards. It also allows a second Normal Summon if one is a Madolche monster, good to use level 4 monster from hand in case there aren't enough on the field to Xyz.
  • Ticket: Any Madolche that returns from Field or GY to Hand or Deck allows to search a Madolche monster to the Hand. If a Fairy Madolche is on the Field, it Special Summons it. Anjelly, Petingcessoeur, Puddingcess, Glassoufle, Tiaramisu and A-la-Mode are all Fairies allowing to Special Summon Messengelato when a Beast type is on the field to find any Madolche Spell/Trap.
  • Chateau: Besides from the obvious 500 ATK/DEF bonus to any Madolche monster, this spell allows to return any Madolches in GY to Deck, triggering effects like Ticket, Salon and A-la-Mode.
Usually, I go Chateau, Salon, Ticket. Bringing Chateau with Messengelato allows to return Anjelly in GY to Deck, triggering A-la-Mode again, detaching Puddingcess to find another Messengelato. With the second one find Salon if you plan on Xyz Summoning Tiaramisu to return things to the opponent's deck for this will trigger Salon and give you access to a Promenade as a protection. If you don't plan or don't have more ways to trigger Madolche's return ability, search Promenade as the protection it gives is imperative if you don't finish the game that turn. As it can be understood, having some Madolches in the GY is good as it allows effects like Promenade, Tiaramisu, Lesson and A-la-Mode. One easy way to put monsters on the grave is Link Summoning Fresh Sistart, giving 2 bodies for the effects. Sistart is herself a way to trigger Salon, Ticket or A-la-Mode as it can prevent being destroyed by returning 1 Madolche monster to the Deck. On other simplier synergies we have Mewfeuille that, when Normal Summoned, Special Summons Messengelato from Hand, searching the Madolche Spells/Traps. Cruffssant can return ANY Madolche card on the field to raise it's level to 4 and gain 300 ATK/DEF, being one of the 2 non-Extra Deck monsters with highest ATK possible (short of Lesson), however careful to not have Sistart pointing to any Madolche as it protects Madolche Spells/Traps even from your own effects (the amount of times I saw myself obligated to return a monster are too many). Lesson serves as a finisher in case you need that extra 800 ATK/DEF to go over your opponent's defenses or another way to return Madolches to the Deck. Regarding non-Madolche cards, Impermanence is a handtrap for turn 1 effects, Called by the Grave stops other handtraps and Twin Twisters destroys Spells/Traps for the price of putting a Madolche in the GY from Hand. Card of Fate is a personal fan card that may or may not give you Petingcessoeur. Abyss Dweller is a GY hate card, Bagooska is a total lockdown for 2 turns, but I play it cause it looks cute, Phoenix is an easy Spell/Trap removal and Almiraj is protection against removal.

deck_description: Strategy for this deck is optimally going for second. You can allow you opponent to setup their boards if you want then disrupt it with Evenly Matched during your turn. If going first, try to setup Evenly Matched, Impermanence, Widow Anchors or Shark Cannon.  Kaiju is for dismantling immovable bricks in opponents board (Ultimateness, Chaos MAX Dragon, etc.)  Deck is standard Sky Striker combos. Search "Sky Striker" Spell Cards using Shizuku. Recycle "Engage" using Kagari. Recycle Kagari using "Herald Base". Hayate for chipping/setting up graveyard.  You can exchange 1 Upstart Goblin for Pot of Avarice for recycling of link monsters (which allows you to link Kagari to recycle Engage or any Sky Striker spell) and gaining card advantage.  Try keep 1 copy of Effect Veiler/Ash in hand for finishing with Accesscode Talker.

deck_excerpt: I used this deck to reach Platinum 1 in Master Duel
deck_description: Disclaimer: Due to lack of resources, my real Master Duel deck only has two copies of Crossout Designator and no Nibiru, while having two copies of Doyon and Bururu instead. I only used a maximum of two copies for staples since I have to balance between survival and potential bricking. If you're going first, you could go into Firewall Dragon Darkfluid with at least two counters and protection (Gatchiri or Light Dragon). If you have a good hand, you could send Water Leviathan into the GY instead of Gatchiri with the Bururu effect, or use AI Love Fusion to bring out Earth Golem as Link material to provide more counters. Along with handtraps and/or quick-play spells, you could shut down many decks provided that they don't have Lava Golem or Kaiju. My past iteration used Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax + Cyberse Quantum Dragon instead of Darkfluid. However, I was traumatized by Tri-Brigade Lyrilusc in the ladder (damn you Shuraig and Draco Future), so I opted for another boss monster. Arrival won't cut it since it is vulnerable to decks that can easily bring out beatsticks like Utopia and even Kaiju (it is expensive to bring out that you can't afford to lose it). If you're going second, you could try to circumvent their defenses to bring out Splash Mage + Update Jammer into Accesscode Talker. You can use Transcode Talker instead of Splash Mage at your own risk, but keep in mind that 4300*2 can win you the game as much as 5300*2. Although, if you need more ammunition for Accesscode, you could go for Transcode. You need to be careful about the placement of your monsters, especially for Dark Templar and Dark Infant. Ideally, Dark Templar must be in the right EMZ with Dark Infant summoned in the leftmost link arrow. The left side of your Dark Infant must also be empty since it will move to that zone after chaining with Dark Templar in order to make way for the special summoned monsters from the GY. Using the effects of Dark Templar and Dark Infant, you can special summon 3 monsters from your GY. It is recommended that you choose Bururu + Pikari (don't use effect yet since it is negated) + 1 (preferably Doyon). Synchro Summon Wind Pegasus (use this as material for Darkfluid since this is very useful in dealing with most invincible monsters even when it is in your GY) using Bururu and Pikari. Pikari will then come back to the field via Bururu's effect. If needed, you can use Pikari's effect to change the level of the other monster to 4 (unnecessary if you have Doyon), then Xyz Summon Light Dragon. Use AI Love Fusion to Fusion Summon Earth Golem using Dark Infant (don't expose a 500 ATK Link monster in the open) and another monster. Note: In another iteration, I would've brought out Cyberse Quantum Dragon instead of Wind Pegasus and Dark Templar + Dark Infant into Avramax, but it is vulnerable to many plays without the means to counter. The most common sequence is Dark Infant >> Cyberse Wicckid (search out Bururu, but skip this if you already have it) >> Splash Mage (don't use its effect if you plan to go into Transcode) >> Transcode Talker (skip this if you used Kaiju) >> Dark Templar. There are many routes and detours to the combo, however, going into Dark Templar while having a monster that can be summoned and Dark Infant in your Extra Deck is the most ideal scenario. One thing to note is that you are expected to utilize Achichi, Pikari, Bururu, and Doyon. Doshin and Hiyari are just luxury monsters that can extend your combo or help you in a pinch. If you find yourself in tough spots, don't ignore the other @Ignister monsters since they have very useful effects. Use Fire Phoenix when you don't have enough cards to continue the combo, since it can float and has a monster destruction effect (during the battle phase, banish Achichi from GY if necessary). Use Wind Pegasus to clean backrow as well as provide a "revenge" mechanism to your board (even in the GY). Use Light Dragon to clean monster zone and resurrect a link monster as soon as you deal battle damage with other Cyberse monsters (works in the battle phase). Use Water Leviathan to reduce a monster's attack to 0 while returning all your link monsters from the GY to the Extra Deck (the other effect doesn't work against most decks since only monsters with 2300 ATK or less are returned to the hand). Earth Golem is usually just fodder for Darkfluid but it could still be useful in some scenarios. The best thing about them is that you can directly resurrect them with AIdle Reborn and FAIghting Spirit, or return them to the hand with Doyon (you can also retrieve related spells with Doyon's effect in the GY). However, if you plan to make use of Dark Templar from the GY, don't resurrect it since it can't be placed in the EMZ this way, instead use Doyon, Water Leviathan, or Doshin (if AI Love Fusion is still in the deck). If you used Kaiju, don't go into Transcode Talker since it won't activate its effect and you'll end up wasting your combo potential. You can see this deck in action on Master Duel. IGN: Allemere ID: 855-035-170

deck_excerpt: A cheap Platinum Rank deck that uses a very consistent shark engine
deck_description:
This deck might seem somewhat unassuming to someone who doesn't have experience with it or anyone who has either never read Number 4: Stealth Kragen or has read it and came away unimpressed; however I have found a lot of success in Platinum Rank with it.   Reasons to play the deck
  1. It's cheap.  Despite the Ultra Rare count seen on this deck, many of those cards are just generic staples (many of which you likely already own) or are cards that can be cut and/or replaced with other similar options.
  2. It's untouchable. You can all but guarantee that nothing in this deck (or at least nothing important) will be touched by a new Master Duel banlist should one come out in the near future.
  3. It's unpredictable. Yugioh players have somewhat of a reputation for not reading cards, and even many who do will miss things like Right-Hand Shark's battle protection. Many of the people you will play against wont have seen much of this deck and wont know how to properly play against it.
Card Explanations 
  • The Fishes (and Tin Goldfish) - You will rarely find a hand in this deck that can't make Number 4: Stealth Kragen even through getting hand trapped and many of them can also throw out an additional rank 4, usually being your choice of Abyss Dweller (which actually benefits nicely from it's attack boosting effect) or Bahamut Shark into Toadally Awesome.  Right-hand Shark's battle protecting will usually either force your opponent to destroy Kragen by a card effect netting you more advantage or will help you survive to OTK your opponent on the crack back. The several two-of's might seem odd but you rarely want or need to see multiples and it's great in combination with White Mirror.
  • The Staples - Play what you have. A huge advantage in playing this deck is that it can comfortably go first when you win the die roll but has plenty of room to play versatile hand traps and "going second" staples. Super Polymerization into Mudragon of the Swamp has extra synergy in this deck since he happens to be a water. Lava Golem might seem like a weird include, but many of your hands don't require your normal summon and this deck often steals games by burning your opponent to death. It's also a super rare. If you already have Forbidden Droplets, Dark Ruler No More, or Evenly Matched, feel free to experiment with those instead.
  • The Extra Deck - The only cards you absolutely need here to play the deck is Number 4: Stealth Kragen and Stealth Kragen Spawn, with close runner-ups being Abyss Dweller with Bahamut Shark with Toadally Awesome. The Floating from your Kragen's easily help you go into Number F0: Utopic Future into Number F0:Utopic Draco Future. Divine Arsenal AA-Zues - Sky Thunder can even by cheesed out by crashing a Kragen or something else protected by Right-Hand Shark into an opponents monster and then overlaying in Main Phase 2. If you have any staple rank 4's like Number 39: Utopia Double or Tornado Dragon, feel free to run them, but remember that some of your shark engine will lock you into water's for the turn.
  • Gozen Match - Number 4: Stealth Kragen turns all monsters your opponent controls into Water's, so Gozen can lock them out of the game. Very few decks are playing any Water's at all. Even without Kragen, it's a pretty solid floodgate on it's own right and basically doesn't effect you. It's also pretty hilarious giving your opponent a Lava Golem going second then flipping Gozen on them on their turn.
As with many decks, feel free to mess around with the ratio's and some spicy techs like Fury of Kairyu-Shin, Xyz Remora, or Number 71: Rebarian Shark. Please let me know if you have any questions, comments, or suggestions regarding the deck.

deck_excerpt: A fun Dragonmaid deck for Master Duel. Good enough to get into Plat, but not quite good enough to make it to the higher levels.
deck_description: Do you want a deck with turns that don't take 40 years? Do you want a deck with combos that don't require 13 steps? Do you want a deck with both cute girls and dragons? Do you want easy wins and to rise to plat 1? Well for that last part you may want to look elsewhere, but for the rest Dragonmaids are the deck for you. The basic plan with this deck is to adapt to going first or second, either getting out Sheou turn one if possible and if not hopefully hieratic and maybe a Dragonmaid Tidying. If going second there's enough hand traps/ board clear to hopefully disrupt your opponets turn enough that they can't respond to your Dragonmaids. Feel free to shift the Maxx C/Ash/Infinites out for your personal favorite field traps/board control, I've just found this combo best handles all but the top 4 decks. Parlor and chamber are the most crucial as they can either get you your fusion spell or put the last monster you need in the graveyard, or shift a tidying in there for a handy special summon. The biggest thing I can recommend is to usually wait as long as possible before activating Sheou's negate. While it is a very handy omni-destruction negate it is a hard once per turn. So even if you manage to trick out another Sheou (which is possible) it won't have its negate until next turn. Its also definitely worth getting either Sheou or House out in Main phase 2 as their effects activate during you opponent's standby phase as well as yours. And lastly try really hard not to get too gung ho about popping the higher level dragon maids back into your hand and putting the low level ones on the field, as if your opponent manages to clear the board before the battle phase you are stuck with a dead hand.  This is a very fun deck with a cool theme, but one that won't see as much success as the current big meta decks. I've managed to get to Plat 3 with it, and can even occasionally take games off Tri-Brigade, Drytron, and Eldlitch but those are few and far in-between.

deck_excerpt: The simps won't see it coming!
deck_description: If going first:  Summon one of your cyberse Live Twin -> Special summon another cyberse Live Twin -> Special summon Treat or Frost (note that you can also use Link Infra-Flier or Parallel eXceed as extenders, in which case your 2nd summon does not have to be cyberse) -> Link Summon both Link Disciple and Link Devotee -> Use Link Disciple effect to tribute Link Devotee -> Link summon I:P Masquerena with the tokens -> Link summon your Evil Twins with Link Devotee and a Live Twin (note that you want to end with Evil Twin Ki-Sikil on the field and Evil Twin Lil-la in the graveyard)  The end board should be I:P Masquerena with your Evil Twins setup. If you summoned your Parallel eXceeds, you may also end with Number 41 on the field.     If going second:  Depending on what your opponent does, respond accordingly with your hand traps.  Usually, you want to go with your usual Evil Twins setup to pick apart your opponent's board.  Use Underworld Goddess of the Closed World to get rid of problematic monsters.  If the board allows you to, you can go for a 4-material Zeus with Sky Cavalry Centaurea and Downerd Magician.     Overall, the deck feels better going second as it allows for more versatility. The deck is also packed with hand traps due to the archetype's small core engine.

deck_excerpt: Crystal Beasts utilizing Rainbow Neos and Ultimate Crystal Magic with an Accesscode Talker package
deck_description: Main focus is Focus on bringing out Rainbow Neos/Overdragon for the win. Bond & Pegasus should mainly search Carbuncle/Pegasus/Eagle other CB's are best left in deck or hand for Ultimate Magic.  If you need to clear back-row with twin twister you can drop a CB and get them back with Pegasus / Emral / Avarice. Having an extra Cobalt Eagle helps protect use of Ultimate magic and Rainbow Dragon, as well as provides access for Chidori. Ecclesia special summons can aid in Syncro for Stardust or Scarlight as well as Link into Lyna, additionally can return to hand if you lose your boss fusion. Using veiler over Ash while less versatile helps provide entry into a combo for Accesscode Talker using Selene & Halqifibrax (Ecclesia can also be used here). Predaplant can assist with bringing out Rainbow Neos. Torrential can combo with Conclave to summon carbuncle and get any backrow CBs available for XYZs/Links. Avarice is here over Blessing as it allows us to get back Neos/Dragon which Crystal blessing would not, Blessing is in side deck to swap in with abundance for possible OTK. Cyclone in Side for Eldlitch. Trap trick in side provides additional way to search for ultimate magic.

deck_excerpt: Powerful OTK going-second deck, "repaired" after the Desires limitation and Nessie release to 3.
deck_description: The last banlist hitting Desires to 1 was not nice to this deck, that aims to OTK the opponent as soon as possible with powerful attackers such as Gren Maju da Eiza or Numeron Dragon, so the list is designed to circunvent that lack of Pots this deck has. It's impossible to run any other Pot card, as Extravagance and Prosperity lock you out of drawing for the turn, and in a list full of Danger! monsters you lose a lot of value. So, instead, I'm maxing out on Eater of Millions, hoping to see it rather consistently in the turns 1 to 4 to combo it with Gren Maju and finish the game right there.  The Danger! engine is quite large, as it takes a hard approach on it, even more since Nessie has been released off the banlist and is now at 3 copies. All the Danger! monsters serve the purpose of digging through your deck, put bodies on the field (especially the level 8 ones, such as Bifgfoot, Thunderbird and Ogopogo) to go into powerful XYZ monsters like Dingirsu, Draglubion (your way to cheat out Numeron Dragon) and Hope Harbinger. Even if the levels don't match, the link monsters in this deck are quite powerful, but I would really consider replacing Zeroboros with Accesscode.  Eater of Millions and Gizmek Orochi are the primary ways to banish cards, obviously including the 1-off Pot of Desires, so it's a 7/40 of cards that banish your deck/extra deck massively. With that in mind, you can't always rely on Gren Maju to OTK, and that's where the XYZ - link monsters enter in the list, as well as huge going-second powerhouses such as Pankratops, Lightning Storm, Feather Duster, Super Poly (with various targets, and specific ones for DIDS and Eldlich) and Nibiru (which is a powerful card even going 1st, don't get me wrong) and even maxing out the going 2nd cards in the side deck, including ones such as Evenly Matched, the 3-off Raigeki, a lone Cosmic Cyclone and Red Reboot.  The deck lacks real consistency, as most of the time the Danger! engine has a RNG component that you sometimes can't play around (and if it fails, you're done) and it can be combined with other cards instead of the ones I chose, such as the Golden Castle of Stromberg package (which not only helps with battle protection and banishing, but also has a LVL8 Special Summon from the deck at the cost of your Normal Summon, and both a MST with legs and field searcher), the full-on banishing cards (adding specifically Dimension Shifter, Macro Cosmos, Dim Fissure and the like) and many other variants that I'm still needing to test in order to make sure they still work as they did before.  Any, I mean, ANY change you make to the deck, please, comment it (if possible), so I can test it myself and maybe improve the deck all together.

deck_excerpt: I use this for Master Duel. It is not good, but I kept winning games, so I didn't want to change it.
deck_description: This deck mainly focuses on Snowdrop the Rikka Fairy. Either to stop opponents combos by destroying monsters with Teardrop the Rikka Queen or go into Draglubion into Numeron Dragon to beatdown the opponent with 9,000 attack. Aromage Marjoram is just good insurance really and for getting rid of Shaddoll's Fusion cards in the graveyard and other decks combo pieces. Gingerbread House is a pretty odd one for a aromage deck, but it helps control the board quite well by getting rid of their bigger monsters during their standby phase. Blessed Winds is saves this deck a lot by recycling cards like Rikka Petal, Lonefire Blossom, and Snowdrop the Rikka Fairy.

deck_excerpt: A Timelord deck with an Eldlich engine that ended up being very stable and could even challenge competitive deck consistently.
deck_description: This deck is an upgrade I made of the Timelord deck when playing Master Duel, I managed to go up to Platinium 4 with this decklist.  You can easily OTK with one timelord (any), and bringing Eldlich to the field, going into Gustav Max, activate its effect for 2000 burn damage then Super Dora at 6000 atk and going for the kill for a total of 8000 damage in one turn. You can also execute this strategy on another turn with the metal slime.  You can also play it as a classic Timelord burn deck as you have all the cards required to do so, you'd want to first attack with michion to bring down the opponent lp to 4000 then finish with either Sandaion, Raphion or Eldlich. Bear in mind that Eldlich is a level 10 monster that also benefit from the protection of Mound of the bound creator and its burn effect.  The addition of the Eldlich engine also allows you to pop problem cards that plagued traditional Timelord deck such as Skill Drain.  Bear in mind though that activating the graveyard effect of Time Maiden or the field effect of Eldlixir of Black Awakenening locks you from playing your extra deck combos, otherwise you're free to play as you want. You should also play the field effect of Eldlixir of Black Awakening at the end of your combo so it doesn't lock you from summoning other monster types.

deck_description: All you need is 3 body with one being a level 4 and the other able to special summon  their self or any blackwing (or "Strangle Lanius") with "Zephyros"...  Step 1. Link summon in to "Wise strix" special summon "Zephyros" if he was not in your open hand otherwise get raider's wing unless you drew "silent boots" than get "Bora the spear"  Step 2. Xyz summon "force strix" with "Zephyros"/"raider's wing" and another lvl 4 monster use "Force Strix" effect  to grab from your deck "Singing Lanius" if already in hand grab "Strangle Lanius" after Force strix" effect goes off "Wise strix" second effect actives grab "Skip force" place on field if "Skip force" in hands grab "soul shave force"  Step 3.  Special summon "singing lanius" first than link summon "Rusty Bardiche" with "Wise strix" and "force Strix"  Step 4. Active "Rusty Bardiche" effect put "Silent boots" in GY place "Magic launch" on field.  Step 5 . Activate "silent boots" from GY get "Shade Brigandine" set than activate right away  Step 6. Xyz summon "Raider's knight" with "Singing lanius and "Shade Brigandine"  Step 7. Activate "Raider's Knight" xyz summon "Blaze Falcon" (if turn 2 you can pop all your opponents special summon)  Step 8. Activate skip force on "Blaze falcon" xyz summon "Arsenal Falcon" activate effect grab "strangle Lanius" if you haven't yet otherwise "Bora the spear"  Step 9. depending on who you grab you can use "strangle Lanius" to grab a Raidraptor monster in GY or "Zephyros" Gy effect to bounce back "Bora" and than special summon "Bora" back. (Note: You can use "Raider's wing" GY ability if you didn't pop the special summons with "Blaze Falcon")  Step 10. Xyz summon "Gagagaga Magician" place him on a spot where "Rusty Bardiche" points to. Activate "Rusty Bardiche's" effect and pop "Arsenal Falcon" (since he has a Raidraptor as material) than activate "Arsenal Falcon GY effect and Special summon "Ultimate Falcon"  Step 11. Detach "Arsenal Falcon" from "Ultimate Falcon"  Step 12. Activate "Gagagaga Magician" to special summon back "Arsenal Falcon" if turn 1 pass if turn 2 activate magic launch select Arsenal Falcon xyz summon "King Kali Yuga" 99% of the time your opponent will just surrender but if not just att for game.  Step 13.  If you were on turn 1 after your opponent play/set his first card activate "magic launch" and watch everything be negated. If they didn't surrender next turn just attack right though them.  Final field: your board should look have "Rusty" "Ultimate Falcon" "Gagagaga Magician" and "Arsenal Falcon "(before magical launch)     Best board you can make: with the other 4 cards you can also get "Full armor master" and "Borreload savage dragon"  Obviously you can do this all on turn 1  #Yu-Gi-OhPlayerDon'tRead

deck_excerpt: The strongest, most competitive Charmer deck I can muster, including cards like Skill Drain and Lord of the Heavenly Prison. Control your opponent, si
deck_description:
https://youtu.be/OfpnygacdOk When the Charmer Structure Deck arrived in the TCG Fall 2020, duelists around the world were hit with disappointment. Highly sought-after staples like Evenly Matched was replaced by cards like Raigeki. The “Charmer” cards were lacklustre and did not do enough to please it’s fans. The promise of a playable Charmer archetype felt like another classic Komoney move – duelist’s expectations were crushed after showing lots of potential. Functioning like a deck from 2010 rather than 2020, the deck had a swarmy beatdown playstyle held up with rickety spell/trap support in the backrow. Dismissed as a “casual DM-era waifu nostalgia bait” structure deck, most duelists neglected the charmers, branding it as one of the worst sets to come out in the TCG. However, several new factors gave indirect support to this ailing archetype! With the new stun/control tools that the 2022 banlist enables, combined with cards from recent sets like Lord of the Heavenly Prison, Incredible Ecclesia, and Zoroa The Magistus Conflagrant Calamity the deck can actually hold its own as a control rogue deck! Functioning a lot like our favourite Golden Boy “Eldlich,” Charming Control stuns out your opponent, sets up multiple interruptions/negates and beats them down with 3000/4000ATK+ monsters! ARCHETYPES AND RATIOS The CHARMER cards in the Main Deck consist of 12 cards: 1 of each of the Familiar-Possessed Charmers (Earth, Water, Fire and Wind), 3 Spirit Charmers, 2 Awakening of the Possessed, 2 Possessed Partnerships and 1 Unpossessed. In the Extra Deck there is 1 of each of the Familiar-Possessed Charmers (Earth, Water, Fire, Wind, Light and Dark). The backrow Charmer Cards serve as the primary core of the deck, serving as its draw engine, recovery, and control. The Extra Deck Charmers give the player a means to link away stolen monsters. The DOGMATIKA cards in the Main Deck consist of 5 cards: 2 Nadir Servant, 1 Ecclesia, 1 Fleurdelis, and 1 Punishment. In the Extra Deck, 2 Elder Entity N’tss and 1 Titaniklad serve as the dump targets for Nadir Servant. The Dogmatika package serve as a potent form of removal, interruption and as an additional way to get extra free bodies on board. The SWORDSOUL cards in the Main Deck consist of 5 cards: 3 Incredible Ecclesia, and 2 The Iris Swordsoul. Both cards serve as free special summons. Incredible Ecclesia opens up synchro plays like Zoroa and Savage Dragon, while Iris Swordsoul is a strong card in itself with its many beneficial effects that offer control and card advantage. The MAGISTUS cards in the Main Deck consist of 3 cards: 3 Zoroa, the Magistus of Flame. Magistus cards have much more presence in the Extra deck, consisting of 5 cards: 2 Artemis, 1 Conflagrant Calamity, 1 Vahram and 1 Aiwass. The Magistus archetype offers a toolbox of options for many situations, but Zoroa usually turbos out level 8 synchro monsters that control the board. Zoroa is a one and a half card Borreload Savage! The STAPLE cards in this deck take up the last 15 slots in this deck. The Staple monsters are 3 Lord of the Heavenly Prison and 3 Fairy Tail – Luna. Both cards are extremely potent for the Charming Control strategy, with Lord of the Heavenly Prison searching out any Spell/Trap (usually Spirit Charmers) and protecting backrow. Luna is low key the MVP of this deck since it fulfills the requirements to trigger Awakening of the Possessed’s +1 draw effect, bounces back opponent’s monsters with it’s quick effect, and searches any 1850ATK spellcaster! The Staple backrow consist of 9 powerful trap cards, each chosen for their synergy with Charmers. 3 Crackdown and 3 Ice Dragon’s Prison interrupt your opponent by stealing their key combo piece monster from their field/GY, which correctly timed, is often enough to end their turn. During your turn, they can be linked away into the appropriate Charmer of choice, then you can again resurrect their monster to your side of the field! 3 Skill Drains are the secret weapon of this deck, and this deck plays perfectly fine with this card on the field! Most interactions/plays that this deck makes is due to backrow support, and once your monsters are supported by Awakening of the Possessed, the game becomes simplified enough where it becomes caveman Yugioh – no effects, no combos, just straight up beatdown! Cool interactions with this card and the deck include The Iris Swordsoul, where she can summon herself from hand for free if monsters on the field are currently negated – a condition that Skill Drain easily fulfills. Incredible Ecclesia can still tribute herself to summon Iris from deck, since her effect activates in the GY, and not on the field. Lord of the Heavenly Prison triggers and resolves IN HAND and not on the field, so it search for your spell/trap of your choice despite Skill Drain being active! Finally, extra deck cards like N’Tss, Titanklad and Vahram trigger in the GY, so they can function well with Skill Drain on the field.   COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN The cool thing about this deck is that it doesn’t feature any combos, since it’s mostly a “set 4 and normal summon -> pass” style of deck, making it pretty simple to use! The entire premise of this deck is to control your opponent with backrow, then beat them in a simplified gamestate, where beatdown with strong superior monsters reign supreme. Depending on your hand, the most ideal turn 1 set-up would be active Charmer Spell/Traps, supported by other generic forms of interruption, like Dogmatika cards, an Borreload Savage, etc. Awakening of the Possessed is the most important card in this case, since it boosts your monster by 300ATK for every attribute on your field, and gives you a +1 draw every time you summon a 1850 ATK spellcaster. This card STACKS, meaning multiple copies of this card can be activated for an even bigger attack boost, so instead of +300 for every attribute, you get +600 if you have two copies! Before you know it, your opponent may be staring down a 3050 ATK charmer and 5200ATK Borreload Savage Dragon! In a grindgame this deck does reasonably well since it generates advantage in various ways. Luna gets you another 1850 spellcaster, Zoroa once equipped with Artemis can search for himself, The Iris Swordsoul gives a +2 draw if your opponent summons from deck and Awakening of the Possessed gets you +1 draw everytime you summon a 1850ATK spellcaster, which is something you’ll do often. If your opponent wipes out your entire backrow, Possessed Partnerships can re-activate a Possessed continuous Spell/Trap from the GY. Finally, all the Extra Deck charmers give you extra monsters on board by reviving your opponent’s monster, and they all float into their attribute appropriate monster from deck! If you anticipate a grindgame, Unpossessed is an ideal card to set-up. ANY monster of yours that would be destroyed will float into a 1500 ATK spellcaster, and that would be any of the Elemental Charmers, Any Ecclesia, and Zoroa! Speaking of Zoroa, that card is a on2 and a half card Borreload Savage Dragon! Here is the only combo this deck features:
  1. Normal Summon Zoroa.
  2. Activate Zoroa’s effect to equip Artemis from Extra Deck to him. His Trigger effect will activate, summoning a level 4 spellcaster from your hand/GY.
  3. Activate Artemis’ searching effect to get you a Magistus monster from deck. It will be Zoroa, so you will have follow-up for next turn.
  4. Synchro away Zoroa + the level 4 spellcaster into Borreload Savage Dragon.
  5. Borreload Savage Dragon equips Artemis from GY, giving you one omni-negate, 1 Zoroa for next turn, and a 3400 ATK monster.
Zoroa can also turn into the Magistus Calamity (Extra Deck-specific floodgate) or Vahram (fieldwipe of opponent’s face up cards).  If you want some immediate damage, you can equip Aiwass to Zoroa instead, giving you a 2500 ATK monster so you can hit over stuff like Winda with a normal summoned monster. After sufficiently softening up your opponent, this deck can easily generate 8000+ ATK, especially with Awakening of the Possessed on the board. This deck features lots of free special summons with high attack monsters such as Iris Swordsoul, Lord of the Heavenly Prison, and the Extra Deck Charmer’s ability to resurrect your opponent’s monster. When the time is right with your field full of Charmers and charmed monsters, SWING FOR GAME!!!   GENERAL TIPS
  • The side deck options offer an expanded array of choices to control the board. Fairy Tail – Snow was recently unbanned, but using her in this deck is almost impossible, as her summoning effect cannot be fulfilled easily. The Dogmatika package can be expanded to include Shadoll cards like Winda and Schism to add an extra power boost at the cost of extra deck slots. Potent field spells like Secret Village and Ichirin are usable with Terraforming, Metaverse and Set Rotation, offering extra control/floodgate control. Finally Emergency Teleport’s target, Ghost Ogre can synchro with another Level 4 Spellcaster to summon Fortune Lady Every, and very strong boss monster.
  • Try to force out a simplified gamestate, where a grindgame is dominant. What this deck lacks in offensive power, it makes up for it in defensive control.
  • This deck can OTK in a blink of an eye, since multiple monsters/attributes on board + Awakening of the Possessed usually generates 10000+ ATK on board.
  • Force out with other cards your opponent’s interaction before using a particularly lethal trap that REALLY hurts your opponent – like Skill Drain (slaughters combo decks) and Ice Dragon’s Prison (banishes Eldlich to the Shadow Realm).
  • This deck obviously prefers to go first. However, trap cards are surprisingly good at breaking apart established boards!
CONCLUDING COMMENTARY Okay okay I’ll admit it, I’m a big sucker and simp for the Charmers, and no matter what I do to help them out, they’ll always remain a casual deck, barely scratching the surface of becoming rogue. This is my personal strongest rendition of this deck using the tools made recently available, and they can actually hold their own versus even the top meta! Not convinced? Watch my Youtube video where Charmers battle Eldlich and Invoked/Shaddol, the Control Kings of the 2022 banlist! (forgive my lame ass video, I haven’t uploaded to Youtube for literal years. I'm gonna give a shot to Yugi-tubing casually, wish me luck!) Seriously though, I love boosting up underpowered and overlooked decks to be able to stand their own ground versus meta, and it’s so utterly satisfying watching a magical girl strike down Eldlich with her astronomically high 3050 ATK! I hope you folks enjoy piloting this deck as much as I do! :) GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: A pretty clean D/D/D decklist that can end on a considerable amount of interruption
deck_description: A pretty clean D/D/D decklist, I'd say. I've been tweaking it for a while, but here's what I play right now. The combos are all intuitive and complicated, so it takes lots of practice to be able to consistently play the deck well. One of the best lines is overlaying Copernicus and Gryphon into Caesar, and then linking off Caesar and another monster (usually Lamia) for Cross-Sheep. This will give you lots of material in grave because the pendulums won't get sent to the extra deck, and it will search Swamp King to trigger the Cross-Sheep with. With this deck, it's pretty important to manage your tuners. Most of your best end board cards are synchros, so you don't want to run out of Lamias. The Ghost is usually your Halqifibrax target. Your Gilgamesh targets are almost always Ragnarok and Apocalypse, unless you want a crazy pendulum summon play I guess. The dragon shrines are all for dumping Destrudo, which is a free extender. It can be used to make Dragster, Alexander, or Halq in a pinch, although you do have to be careful not to burn yourself out. I'm choosing to main deck Eternal Darkness, because I think the lock is a bit better than Patent License, but you can side Eternal Darkness out for it if that's better. The side deck and hand traps are flexible of course, but I think these are pretty good for this format. Enjoy!

My Numeron themed deck from Master Duel.
deck_description: Any card in my hand that allows me to add or activate Numeron Network is used. I then activate Numeron Network's effect to activate Numeron Calling, allowing me to Special Summon Numbers 1-4 on my field. If Memories of Hope is on my hand, then I activate it allowing me to draw 4 cards since 4 Xyz monsters are on the field. I then Xyz Summon Number C1: Numeron Chaos Gate Sunya using Number 1 as Xyz material. Sunya's effect banishes all monsters on the field. If Swift Scarecrow is in my hand, then I do not summon any monsters for the rest of the turn, because Swift Scarecrow can be immediately sent to my graveyard if my opponent declares a direct attack. In doing so, the battle phase immediately ends, negating the direct attack. I then Special Summon Sunya during my next Standby Phase with it's effect. Then the opponent takes 1000 LP worth of damage for each of my banished monsters. If I have Foolish Burial Goods, then I use it to send a Numeron Network from my deck to my graveyard. I then activate one of my monster effects from cards such as Exiled Force, Unchained Twins Aruha, etc, to destroy my Chaos Gate Sunya, and send it to my Graveyard. I then activate Numeron Network's effect to send Numeron Chaos Ritual to my graveyard. This allows me to use any 4 Xyz monsters + Numeron Network in my graveyard or banished, to Xyz summon Number C1000 Numeronius. It gains 10,000 ATK if summoned this way. If it is destroyed by an opponents card effect, I then Xyz summon Number iC1000 Numeronius Numerounia from my Extra Deck and attatch Numeronius to it as Xyz material. Numerounia gains 100,000 ATK/DF if Summoned this way only during the opponent's turn.

deck_description: The Dark Magician Deck I play IRL The deck follows the standard Dark Magician starts of playing Dragoon but uses the new Battle of Chaos cards. Generally, you would probably play 2-3 Illusion of Chaos (You can probably go down to 1 or 2 Timaeus), I only pulled 1 and it's still worth running at 1 since it's super easy to search since you can use Soul Servant to top deck it and draw (which you can search for with circle and rod), then immediately activate it and just keep it in your hand forever grabbing whatever DM monster you want.  If you have the cards another Dragoon you can remove Dark Cavalry for it.  I generally side out Magician's Nav, Eye of Timaeus and one of the Timaeus Dragons for the general set of 2-3 cards that I would want depending on matchup.

deck_excerpt: Fun Deck Possessed Charmer. Low budget Deck. 3x Spirit Charmer Structure Deck and some support (dark/light Monsters, 3x Eda, Extradeck)
deck_description: Try to get as many monsters with different attributes on your field as possible to increase your atk. Get Awakining of the Possessed and 1 Possessed Monster with Spirit Charmers. If you already have one of these or both take a second Awakining of the Possessed and/or Unpossessed.  Summon Nefariouser Archfiend asap from your deck and special summon a monster from gy with an attribute that is not already on the field. If possible summon a (Possessed) Link Monster to activate Nefariouser Archfiend second effect to get another Awakining of the Possessed (alternativ Unpossessed or Possessed Partnerships) and get the best Monster from your oppenents gy. Afterwards if you need you can summon Decode Talker or Knightmare Unicorn. With Eda the Sun Magician choose a Monster with a new attribute or a Charmer Monster with the attribute of 1 of your oppentens (best) Monster. Summon Gagigobyte, Rasenryu and Inari from your deck if you need them. While they are in your hand and you don't need them, use them for twin twister, spirit charmers or Grand Spiritual Art. In this deck are Monsters of all attributes. If you know what deck your oppenent is playing, put out all Charmer Monsters in Maindeck and Possessed Monster in Extradeck with the attribute your oppenent is not playing with. Put it more counter cards like Solemn Warning, Dark Ruler Nomore, Effectveiler, Dimensionbarrier etc.. In Extradeck you can also play Utopia, Castel or Daigusto.

deck_excerpt: You have heard of Danger! Darkworld but Infernity cards and Dark world cards?
deck_description: Use the power of Infernity cards to discard your own hand and trigger off Dark world monsters like Grapha, Dragon lord of Dark World to pop an opponents card (Although you probably won't be doing that turn 1 which this deck thrives on). If you like to play hand traps, some good cards to cut are: Infernity Barrier (As it is a negate but a trap with strict activation) 1 Copy of Graph (Because you don't want to draw it turn 1) 1 Copy of Archfiend (The deck works fine with 2)   The main cards that I suggest you don't change the amounts of are: Infernity Conjurer (This card is a crazy good combo piece) because of its SS from GY effect (https://yugioh.fandom.com/wiki/Infernity_Conjurer) Infernity Inferno because it is a great way to discard Dark worlds and send combo pieces like Conjurer to the grave (https://yugioh.fandom.com/wiki/Infernity_Inferno) Infernity Sage (Also an insane combo piece) because once per turn you can discard (triggering DW effects) your entire hand. Also while you have no cards in hand when it is sent to the gy (By foolish burial, Battle, Card effect, Sync/Link summon) while you have no cards in hand, you can send an additional infernity to the GY. (https://yugioh.fandom.com/wiki/Infernity_Sage) I do play this deck on Master Duel and it is quite fun. Anyway, Enjoy the decklist!

deck_excerpt: New Pendulum Magician deck taking advantage of Astrograph Sorcerer & Fairy Tail - Snow. Make sure to read my notes and watch the combos video. For f
deck_description: First, you can make changes to the Extra Deck to match the current Meta since Link Evolution misses cards. You can add Accesscode Talker, Baronne de Fleur and Artemis, the Magistus Moon Maiden in place of Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon, Ultimaya Tzolkin and Clara & Rushka, the Ventriloduo.  Some cards in this deck provide means to play through interruptions. Fairy Tail - Snow can banish 7 cards from Hand, Grave and/or Field to Special Summon itself. Let's say your Tornado Dragon or Artifact Scythe is being negated, you can simply banish whichever is being negated and resolve the effect. You can send Fairy Tail - Snow to Grave through Timestar Magician. Fairy Tail - Snow can also be used to interrupt the 1st summon of the opponent.  You can also do the same with Time Pendulumgraph, but you need to have Timestar Magician on the Field. Using Time Pendulumgraph and Timestar Magician, we can play through 2 interruptions. Let's say Tornado Dragon is being negated by Infinite Impermanence (We need a card on your opponent Field for this to work), chain Time Pendulumgraph and activate its effect. Select 1 Pendulum card in your Pendulum Scale and Infinite Impermanence. Timestar Magician will then trigger its effect to protect the Pendulum card by sending 1 card to Grave and that card is Fairy Tail - Snow. Since only 1 card was destroyed, Time Pendulumgraph will activate its effect to send 1 card on the field to Grave, so send Tornado Dragon and that's how you dodge the Infinite Impermanence. Now, Artifact Scythe is on the field since Tornado Dragon's effect resolved. When Artifact Scythe tries to activate, let's say you opponent tries to negate it. Simply, chain Fairy Tail - Snow banishing 7 cards from Hand, Grave and/or Field including Artifact Scythe to dodge the negation once again.  Regarding the combo in Duel 1, instead of summoning a lvl 4 using Harmonizing Magician's effect, summon Oafdragon Magician and Synchro Summon Baronne de Fleur instead of Ignister Prominence, the Blasting Dracoslayer. The link 1 is used to send Fairy Tail - Snow to Grave in the off chance she's your only summon, so you can use her as an interruption.  In the gameplay, I once opted to not use Astrograph Sorcerer's effect after I destroyed a card I control thinking I can add it using Oafdragon Magician (It can only add 1 face-up "Magician" or "Odd-Eyes" Pendulum Monster from your Extra Deck to your hand). The correct way would have been to Pendulum Summon, XYZ Timestar Magician, Synchro Summon Baronne de Fleur OR XYZ Tornado Dragon, Link Astrograph Sorcerer with another card into Artifact Dagda and use Timestar Magician's effect to add Astrograph Sorcerer from the Extra Deck. Use Baronne de Fleur OR Tornado Dragon to destroy the scale (Don't protect using Timestar Magician) and Special Summon Astrograph Sorcerer from your hand and add a card from deck. The rest depends on your hand.  Props to Trif Gaming for the combos and the profile.  https://youtu.be/FTiH845roOY

deck_excerpt: *Insert raiding gender joke here*
deck_description: (I don't know why it took me this long to submit a deck of my favorite deck of all time but oh well)  Have you ever played Pacifis control and thought "Man I wish I had bricks to keep the gameplay fresh"? Well look no further because Generaider is here (and has been for a while but let's not talk about that). This deck is one of those classic field spell centric decks that has zero way to play when the field spell is somewhere other than on board. But unlike those decks, you're running a huge amount of level 9s that really want to stay in deck for the deck to function. However, Generaiders have some extremely good support to make up for this inherent weak spot that makes them semi-consistent and an absolute king of the mid-game.  There are 9 main deck monsters in the archetype and really only 6 are worth talking about. Harr, Hela, Utgarda, and Nidhogg all have the usual Generaider effects where they tribute monsters for a beneficial effect. Harr is an omni-negate, Hela is a reborn, Utgarda is a targeting banish, and Nidhogg is a summon negate. Mardel and Loptr are a bit unique in the deck as Mardel is your search card when summoned and Loptr tributes any Generaider on board (including itself) for a level 9 Generaider from deck. Loptr is also the only normal summon in the deck, so all you Aleister fanboys can go wild. Naglfar, Frodi, and Dovelgus are all really really bleh compared to the rest, so don't run them unless you feel super confident in your ability to draw like Lithium when he plays Monarchs.  As for ratios of the main deck Generaiders, 3 Mardel and 3 Loptr is standard with one or two of the others depending on what you think you'll need in the deck. Trias Hierarchia is also a really good inclusion in the deck as it can tribute your Generaider tokens to summon itself on your opponent's turn. If you include that, run 2 or 3 copies as it is always online if you have access to the field spell.  Onto the spell cards, Boss Stage is the heart and soul of the deck. It kinda defines the whole playstyle of Generaiders, that being playing during your opponent's turn but in a cooler way than PSY-Frames could ever hope to achieve. It summons tokens during their turn that enable every Generaider to pop off, and it summons one from deck before doing so. Just the coolest field spell in the game in my opinion. Run three because you have to.  To find the field spell we have 7 additional backrow (plus Mardel) to find it. Terraforming is Terraforming and it just does Terraforming things. I'd run three if I could, but you kinda can't and probably never will be able to again. RIP in kill sweet prince. Boss Quest searches two Generaider spells and traps with different names for the low, low cost of putting a brick back in the deck. You run three and only ever three. Boss Fight activates Boss Stage from the deck or GY. It's like Metaverse but better. Run three. Boss Room is a really cool card that changes any activated effect into both players drawing one card. I usually run three, but with Boss Quest it's almost always accessible so you can run one or two instead.  The non-Generaider backrow is pretty self-explanatory. Pot of Avarice keeps you in the game longer than 11 turns which might not ever come up if the people you play against are always on combo decks, but I always end up playing against Dark Magician or Geist 90% of the time so it's nice to have this card in the deck. Kuji-Kiri Curse is an additional unbricking tool that also sets up Hela while drawing two cards. You can run Prosperity instead, but you do want your extra deck to help close out games. World Legacy's Monstrosity is an amazing card in the deck as it can either summon one level 9 from your hand or summon two from deck if you have one on board already. Other than just simply waiting for Boss Stage to activate a few times, this is how you get into the extra deck. Rank-Up Magic Argent Chaos Force is a bit of a sussy include, but I lost a game to geist while being 100 LP from winning, so this enables you to summon this deck's version of "Cowboy for game" being Number C9.  The extra deck is just every single good rank 9 you can run with some links to help with using Loptr as material when your deck is running low on cards. Heart-eartH is my favorite xyz monster in the game, and could absolutely be replaced by something better, but it's included here because I really like the card. Tachyon Dragon helps close out games with its skill drain effect. Enterblathnir is just really good answer to a lot of problem cards with its non-targeting banish. Dyson Sphere is good at cleaning up games by attacking directly (and then you can rank it up to really close out a game). Hyperyton brings even more negates to the party in the weirdest way possible. The Cat is another Hela but without the tribute cost. Jormungandr is technically the boss monster of the deck and can steal your opponent's resources to achieve big number.  The Knightmares are standard and don't need explaining. World Gears, however, is probably the worst deckbuilding choice I have ever made. If you summon this card, it clears the board, which sounds super cool. But Generaiders kinda want the board so they can build up advantage turn by turn and exhaust their opponent. Not to mention if you manage to get 3 level 9's on board, you can access the entire extra deck (except the chaos xyz cards) instead of a field nuke towers. It might be better than I make it out to be, but I've never had it work for me.  In the side deck, Lava Golem is a solid choice with how few normal summons the deck has. Kaijus might be better in most cases, but Enterblathnir can usually handle a single boss monster on its own. Raigeki is Raigeki and it's just better lightning storm now that it's unbanned. Cosmic Cyclone is a good answer to other spell reliant decks and Heavy Storm Duster does the same but while dodging Anti-Spell and Imperial Order (Not anymore though, get fucked IO). Imperm is just my favorite handtrap with how effective it is going first or second, but you can use any other hand traps you'd like.  This definitely isn't the best build of the deck out there, but I'm not a huge fan of mixing archetypes together so this is the best I can make while keeping it pure. You can add Girsu, Therizia, or Aleister and their engine cards to give the deck more normal summons and either extension or boss monsters, or use a Guru deck as the base and splash in Generaider if you're a streamer who's beyond high on copium. If you have any questions or suggestions, leave them below so I can try and improve the deck as best as I can.

deck_excerpt: Elpy is still grounded.
deck_description: Dragon Link is a powerful combo deck that aims to go first and set up disruption, but can also OTK going second through its easy access to Borrelsword Dragon. It excels at playing through your opponent's disruption through the use of chain blocking. Your main starters are Black Metal Dragon, Starliege Seyfert, and Chaos Space. These cards can give you access to additional monsters while chain blocking your most important effects. For instance, if you have Black Metal Dragon and a Rokket monster in hand, you can use Black Metal Dragon to link summon Striker Dragon. Then, since both monsters' effects activate at the same time, you can decide what order they will occur in the chain. Your opponent will only be able to respond to the last card activated in the chain. By making Striker Dragon chain link 1 and Black Metal Dragon chain link 2, your opponent cannot use a card like Ash Blossom to negate your Striker Dragon's effect. Therefore, you can successfully add Boot Sector Launch and use it to summon the Rokket monster from hand. To play through interruption optimally, you will have to decide which effects to chain block based on what cards you have in hand and what situation you are in. Here are a few basic combos you can go through. #1 Black Metal Dragon Normal Summon Black Metal Dragon > Link Summon Striker Dragon > Activate Both Effects To Search Boot Sector Launch And Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon(RedMD) > Banish Striker Dragon To Special Summon RedMD > Activate RedMD's Effect To Special Summon Black Metal Dragon From Grave > Use RedMD And Black Metal Dragon To Link Summon Dragunity Knight Romulus And Activate The Effects Of Romulus And Black Metal Dragon To Add Dragon Ravine And Another RedMD > Activate Dragon Ravine And Discard 1 Card To Activate Its Effect To Send Absorouter Dragon To Grave > Activate Absorouter's Effect To Add Rokket Tracer > Activate Boot Sector Launch And Use Its Effect To Special Summon Rokket Tracer > Activate Rokket Tracer's Effect To Destroy Romulus And Special Summon Rokket Recharger Or Silverrokket From Deck > Synchro Summon Borreload Savage Dragon And Use Its Effect To Equip Romulus #2 Chaos Space + 1 Dark Monster Activate Chaos Space And Send A Dark From Hand To Grave To Search White Dragon Wyverburster > Banish The Dark Monster From Grave To Summon Wyverburster > Link Summon Striker Dragon And Activate Both Effects To Search Boot Sector And Black Dragon Collapserpent > Banish Wyverburster To Summon Collapserpent > At This Point You Can Activate The Effect Of Chaos Space In Grave To Place Wyverburster On The Bottom Of Your Deck And Draw 1 Card > Use Striker Dragon And Collapserpent To Link Summon Romulus And Activate The Effects Of Romulus And Collapserpent To Search Dragon Ravine And Wyverburster > Activate Dragon Ravine And Use Its Effect To Discard Wyverburster, Or Any Card In Hand That You Don't Need Or That You Want In Grave, And Send Absorouter To Grave > Activate Absorouter To Search Rokket Tracer > Activate Boot Sector Launch And Use Its Effect To Special Summon Rokket Tracer From Hand > Use Tracer's Effect To Destroy Romulus And Special Summon A Level 4 Rokket From Deck > Synchro Summon Borreload Savage Dragon And Equip Romulus *this can also be performed by using a light monster with chaos space to search collapserpent first *also note that this is performed without the use of your normal summon **you could also perform this combo with only starliege seyfert and 1 discard by using seyfert to search collapserpent, but it would use your normal summon and wouldn't get you the draw #3 Black Metal Dragon + Noctovision Dragon + 1 Rokket Monster Normal Summon Black Metal Dragon > Link Summon Striker Dragon > Activate The Effects Of Striker Dragon, Black Metal Dragon, And Noctovision Dragon To Search Boot Sector Launch, Search Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon, And Special Summon Noctovision From Hand > Banish Striker Dragon To Special Summon RedMD > Use RedMD's Effect To Special Summon Black Metal Dragon From Grave > Use Noctovision And Black Metal Dragon To Link Summon Romulus And Use The Effects Of Romulus, Black Metal Dragon, And Noctovision To Search Dragon Graveyard For Future Plays) > Use Chaos Ruler, The Chaotic Magical Dragon And Rokket Synchron To Synchro Summon Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss #4 Black Metal Dragon + Quick Launch + 1 Rokket Monster Dragon To Summon Wyverburster > Use Striker Dragon And Wyverburster To Link Summon Hieratic Seal Of The Heavenly Spheres > Activate Wyverburster To Add Collapserpent > Banish Wyverburster To Summon Collapserpent > Use Collapserpent To Link Summon Another Striker Dragon And Place It In The Zone That Spheres Bottom Right Link Arrow Points To > Activate Collapserpent To Add Wyverburster > Activate Boot Sector And Use Its Effect To Special Summon Tracer And Recharger From Hand > Use Tracer To Link Summon Guardragon Pisty In The Zone That Spheres Bottom Left Link Arrow Points To > At This Point You Will Have Striker Dragon And Pisty Positioned To Both Point At The Same Zone, So You Can Use Pisty's Effect To Special Summon Tracer From Grave To That Zone > Banish Striker Dragon To Summon RedMD > Use RedMD To Summon The Striker Dragon That Is In Grave > Use RedMD, Striker Dragon, Pisty, And Recharger To Link Summon Saryuja And Activate Its Effect To Draw 4 Cards Then Return 3 Cards From Your Hand To The Bottom Of The Deck (by This Point You Will Have Thinned Out Your Deck A Good Bit So You Can Find Hand Traps And Board Breakers, And Setup Your Hand For Future Turns) > From Here You Can Use Tracer's Effect To Destroy Saryuja And Special Summon A Recharger Or Silverrokket From Deck > Synchro Summon Borreload Savage Dragon And Equip Saryuja These combos outlined should give you a basic idea of how the deck is played. Throughout your turn, you will ideally gain access to even more plays through the cards you draw and excavate. As you get more familiar with the deck, you will see many other combo lines that you can go through. The usual end board is spheres + hot red dragon archfiend abyss, spheres + borreload savage dragon, or sometimes all 3. Spheres functions as both disruption and a way to search levianeer by summoning brotaur off its second effect. By this point you will have already filled your graveyard with the necessary requirements to summon it when your opponent passes turn. It can then be used to help break the board they set up if they managed to play through your disruption. Some things to keep in mind: *Rokket Tracer's effect will lock you into summoning dark monsters from the extra deck for the rest of the turn. *Rokket Synchron's effect will lock you into summoning dark monsters from the extra deck for the rest of the turn. *Black Metal Dragon is not once per turn. *Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Spheres can only activate its effect to return a card to hand while in an extra monster zone. *When tributing itself for cost, Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Spheres can resolve its effect to return a card to hand while under skill drain, because it won't be on the field during resolution. *Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Spheres does not target. You will choose which face-up card to return to hand when resolving its effect. *Nibiru will trigger Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Spheres effect to special summon a dragon from deck. *Rokket Tracer's effect is a quick effect, so you can chain it to the activation of one of your spell cards, and destroy that spell card, to get both effects without having to sacrifice an additional resource. *White Dragon Wyverburster and Black Dragon Collapserpent's effect to special summon themselves from hand is once per turn, but their effect to add each other is not.
