deck_excerpt: Discussion about one of my favorite decks since I started playing Yu-gi-oh!
deck_description: My goal is to discuss why you should remember Mathmech as a Salamangreat-style Cyberse midrange deck and not a Crusadia-style OTK deck just because you have the Final Sigma win button. Many of the games have a grind game of more than 5 turns so much more important than trying to OTK at all costs with this deck is to exchange resources efficiently which is very easy to do thanks to the absurd cards called Mathmech Superfactorial and Laplacian that are a potential -3 to even -4 for the opponent counting the Mathmech Diameter omni negate. Not to mention that archetype XYZ monsters are excellent and even a little stolen when reading for the first time, Alembertian being a Searcher and Extender and Laplacian a Trishula that can be given on the opponent's turn. An interesting point about Mathmech's Extra Deck monsters is that they are generic and can be used in almost any deck. I myself am sure that someday there will be a deck to abuse Alembertian absurd effects when made with 3 materials or 4 materials. /////////////////////////////////////////                                                                                                                                                                                                                    Decklist picks: The Mathmech archetype cards such as Synchro level 8, Equip's spell and Reborn's spell and Trap which is a pop don't do much for the deck and therefore are not part of the decklist. Generic Cyberse support like Lady Debug and Cynet Mining are cards that take up consistency card slots and hand traps so in the end they don't do much for deck strategy. Cynet Mining doesn't have good discards in the deck and you don't need these cards to play Mathmech after all. ///////////////////////////////////////// Recommended cards: Mathmech's deck in the TCG enters this February format with a lot more consistency issues because of the Pot of Desires limitation and one card that can help the deck is Triple Tactics Talents which is a very versatile card. Another card that I highly recommend using in the deck is Topologic Zeroboros because it's very easy to trigger its effect and clear the opponent's field by going second. /////////////////////////////////////////Combos: This topic is not really a tutorial on how to play each specific hand, but plays I made with a random hand that I opened playing with the deck. It's a nice way to show the deck's proposal from where it wants to go, considering how you would start your moves and the play lines chosen. The important thing is to understand that this is a deck that does not tolerate errors during gameplay, so you should always be aware of the most efficient way to play. These examples that I show you along with the technoplay tips that I talk about after these combos are enough to get you started playing Mathmech. As you can see these combos are narrations of how I played with a certain hand and how I behaved after taking interactions like hand traps and from the opponent's established fields as well. From the End Board you can see that the objective is to pass with the Superfactorial trap along with 3 Mathmech Monsters in the GY with different names including the Diameter which turns the Xyz Mathmech into an omni negate as well. For this we use the Link Disciple + Link Devotee combo to access Link-2 Wicckid that adds the Diameter/Nabla needed to make the Alembertian that adds the Trap Superfactorial at the same time that it finishes the necessary names in the gy. //////////////////////////////////////////// Combo 1: Diameter + Sigma Sigma eff SS from HAND and NS Diameter RANK-4 Alembertian(have 1 Negate) and eff Add to keep a card in hand for the Knightmare Unicorn) ////////////////////////////////////////////// Combo 17: Sigma + Subtraction + Addition (Blind Second) =Hard Make Final Sigma SS Subtraction and SS Addition and SS Sigma SYNCHRO 12 Final Sigma ///////////////////////////////////////////// Technoplay cards of Main Deck: Balancer Lord + any Mathmech is a full combo with Nabla tribute Linguriboh bringing the Diameter from the deck to make Alembert and add the Superfactorial and pass. You always use the Balancer Lord effect from Extra Normal Summon and save to use only the normal summons of good cards that are the basics of the deck save the Normal Summons for the right cards. Diameter allows your Mathmech boss monsters to be omni negate to interact with the opponent or negate cards like Nibiru on your turn. Whenever you open it with Diameter you want to throw a monster in the gy to take advantage of its Normal Summon. So much so that even if you draw from Balancer Lord + Diameter, you doing this play do very well. However you have to analyze if your hand is too weak for interactions because in that case a negate in the Mathmech Diameter makes your turn end. You have to remember that Alembertian is guaranteed to search for negate so it is always safe to go straight to it with Diameter. Mathmech Nabla is a fundamental piece to access the missing monster to make the Superfactorial alive in the opponent's turn, especially the Diameter but it can be Sigma if you already have access to the Diameter. If you open from Nabla and Diameter but you can't have a monster in the GY, the best thing is to use Nabla from NS and use eff SS Diameter from Deck and keep the Diameter in hand as Follow Up. If you can use Multiplication/Nabla as Xyz material on your next turn if you Tribute Xyz with the effect of Nabla or Alembertian it trigger eff to double ATK/Monster can make two attacks which is cool if the monster you make is Accesscode for example. Important to know the right choices of how to start hand summons, see the details to have plays after interactions mainly going second. When you open with RANK-4 Alembertian play and Extender you can start adding a Superfactorial and then go to play Link Disciple and Devotee and Wicckid combo. But this is not an orthodox play and it might be good to first go to Wicckid turbo play to gain access to Diameter to ensure Alembertian will resolve and add Superfactorial. Primary Follow Up is adding Diameter and secondary is adding Nabla/Sigma. Cool is that if you already open with Superfactorial, use Alembertian to add Extenders or Nabla to access Diameter and try to generate an advantage with Link Disciple and Link Devotee moves etc. If you can stop the opponent without having to use the Superfactorial, it's very good to leave it to use it only on your turn because in addition to the mini Trishula you get right at the beginning of the Diameter's negate turn to play safe your turn. You only activate on his turn with him doing nothing that threatens you if he sets a trap on the same column as the Superfactorial because it will most likely be an Infinite Impermanence. Many times you want to play Accesscode Turbo and even then you don't have a chance to OTK it and so using two Superfactorial and two Laplacian is essential. It's important to understand that this is not an OTK deck so using the second trap in matches plus grind game is fundamental, looking at the gamestate and predicting the best move is essential in decks that are based on trading resources and for everything I've played with this deck you always take the game to a simplified gamestate. Always try to play around Forbidden Droplet when you have I:P Masquerena + Superfactorial on the field because first you must use I:P Masquerena eff and if he negates with Droplets you will still have the Superfactorial summon Laplacian. If you take Called By The Grave in the Superfactorial eff on one of the 3 targets in the gy you will still be able to summon the other two targets and do the Alembertian at least to add a Follow Up and if you have the Diameter as material have an omni negate also. Only if the opponent banishes at least 2 targets from the Superfactorial that it doesn't resolve. Parallel eXceed does not trigger eff if MASTER DUEL game button is Off. If you are facing a deck that uses Skill Drain, summon Parallel eXceed in Attack Position because if your opponent uses Skill Drain the eXceed returns to 2k atk and at least you will have a monster with great attack to try to survive until you take the Skill Drain that can be done with even Accesscode using effect and banishing itself from the field as cost. Of the Deck Extenders: Addition, Subtraction and Mathmech Sigma you should pay attention to the card details that first all of them lock you from Special Summoning Cyberse monsters from the Extra Deck for the rest of the turn. Second that Sigma is the best extender of the 3 because it is searchable by Wicckid since it is Tuner and being able to come back from GY has the detail of being banned when leaving the field so the only way to not have it banned is to use it as xyz material but it doesn't make much difference to have him banned for his turn 1 combo to pass. Addition and Subtraction cannot declare an attack in the turn that are Special Summoned by their own effect and they can target opponent's monsters whatever better the deck to go second and break the field. Against Decks Blind Second = This deck doesn't care about many of the cards used to break the field. For example Lightning Storm on monster doesn't affect the deck at all because of Wicckid and Laplacian and Dark Ruler No More at best takes the interaction from I:P Masquerena only. Evenly Matched is another card that the deck handles easily. The best blind second card against Mathmech is the Forbidden Droplet. ///////////////////////////////////////////// Technoplay cards of Extra Deck: Laplacian doesn't destroy the cards but sends them to the GY so you can take spells/traps out of the field on the protection of Heavenly Sky or the Golden Lord that came back from the GY by its own effect. Alembertian on the Following turn is usually to add extenders to kill the opponent whether Sigma or Nabla bring Multiplication from the deck and do FINAL SIGMA or Accesscode Talker Turbo or continue controlling the game with Superfactorial. *(Don't FORGET that LINK DEVOTEE has a MANDATORY Eff to ACTIVATE when he ENTERS the FIELD to LOCK you into CANNOT SUMMON LINK-3 or Higher) ***Place the tokens in the zones away from the Links arrows. Linguriboh protects Wicckid from being negated by Trap cards like Infinite Impermanence. Against backrow matchups they are insane too. LINK-2 Cyberse Wicckid is an absurd card that is a fundamental piece for the deck to spin and you access the cards you need to make your turn 1 setup and even generate follow up on your opponent's turn by activating Superfactorial and bringing 1 of the Mathmech from gy in the zone it points to (it doesn't have to be the XYZ in Wicckid's zone to trigger its effect). COOL INTERACTION: WICCKID + SUPERFACTORIAL = You don't need to bring XYZ to the field in the Wicckid zone, but the Reborn of the GY is one in the Wicckid zone and even then you in the new chain link can use Wicckid cl1 Laplacian cl2. As long as Wicckid is on the field you can generate plus and add Mathmech Tuners to the hand every turn. Wicckid protecting the Cyberse he points out from Destruction is also absurd. See what is really going to banish from gy as cost of Wicckid because you don't want to banish Mathmech level 4 monsters and if possible you want to also keep the Links in gy so that your Accesscode has multiple pops so if you have XYZ Alembertian and Laplacian at GY banning them is always free. A very interesting play is to use Wicckid's absurd effect in your favor when you open it going second to force interactions because if you do Wicckid with eXceed in your hand, you practically get to Accesscode without losing to cards that destroy, that is, guaranteed to force interactions . It happens a lot to use I:P Masquerena to Accesscode on the opponent's turn in trap matches already to start your turn by destroying the opponent's backrow with an Accesscode of 4300atk that cannot be destroyed by effects. When opponent uses Dogmatika Maximus effect you always send I:P Masquerena + Unicorn to GY. (remember to keep a card in hand for Knightmare Unicorn - a very simple detail to remember for I:P Masquerena to work) One cool thing about this deck is the ability to Accesscode with a lot of extra effects like Attack twice or Doubled ATK which is really good.

deck_excerpt: I just reached Platinium 1 with this deck, here's the deck list.
deck_description: I just reached Platinium 1 with this deck, here's the deck list. 10 handtraps, 10 draw power, 20 other cards, balanced, as all things should be. Blind 2nd, use handtraps and spell cards to outplay opponents.   Reasons for NOT playing some of commonly played cards: Infinite impermanence: Too many effect negations already, effect veiler, fobidden chalice, widow anchor. Raigeki, lightning storm: Most monsters have floating effect or proections nowdays, these cards might sometimes brick you. Pot of Avarice: This card sometimes brick, you cannot use it turn one. Ghost belle, Droll & lock bird, Ghost ogre, Gamma: Not generic enough, sometimes brick. Call by the grave & Shark Cannon & Crossout Designator: Not all decks use monsters in graveyard, sometimes brick. Upstar goblin: Chicken's game is better, sky strikers have a hard time OTKing opponent with more than 8K LP,  Accesscode & 2 sky striker monsters can only output 8K damage. Kaiser Colussum & There can only be one: Mostly useless if not going first. Foolish Brial Goods & Metalfoe Fusion & Toon table of content: Bricks more than it helps. Knightmare phoneix: cannot use it to out skill drain, imperial order is at 1 and rarely seen, not worth it. Harpie feather duster, other S&T removal: If Eldlich didn't open skill drain and imperial order, these are not really needed.   Reasons for playing some of the cards: 2 Nibiru: Not 3 by reducing chances of bricking, but high enough for opening & maxx c into it. 2 Veiler: Not 3 because it might brick, need at least 2 for accesscode play. Borrelsword: To beat off some "unaffected by card effects" boss monsters. 2 Pot of desires: Not 3 because, A, you don't want desires into desires, B, you can't really use 2 since you only have 40 cards in your deck. Eagle Booster: Good for preventing OTKed by opponent, use it on accesscode and win next turn. Imperial iron wall: Hurt most decks and help yourself. Drytron: cannot use eva to +2. Tri-brigade: no banishing to summon & link-4 removal. Gren-maju: dead. VW: shenshen effect useless. Eldlich: cannot go +1 off of traps in grave. Cyber dragon: cannot fusion summon. Invoked Shadoll: invoked summon play got hindered.  Generic: Stops accesscode, callby the grave and crossout designator, DD crow, Most Pots. With Multirole & Impeiral iron wall, you can loop your spells infinitely, gaining unfair advantage. You can also get rid of it with multirole if it hinders you.

deck_excerpt: A fun deck that I used to climb to Platinum on Master Duel* and one I also use in real life
deck_description: As the name implies, this deck focuses on being able to turbo out Toadally Awesome turn 1 and contains lots of rank 4s that can be special summoned to achieve this. Ideally on turn 1 you want to bring out Bahamut Shark to detach a material and then summon Toadally Awesome. Having Defender of the Ice Barrier with another Ice Barrier monster on field is also great since it stops your opponent from declaring an attack (as long as their monsters have attack greater than 1600). On turn 2 you will want to summon out either Trishula Zero Dragon of the Ice Barrier or regular Trishula to remove cards with its' non-targeting banishing effect. Usually, if my opponent has 3 or more cards I will try to summon Zero Dragon, and if they have only one card on the field I will summon out regular Trishula so I can also banish cards from their hand and graveyard too.  If you manage to draw Gozen Match on turn one then this is a great time to summon Number 4: Stealth Kragen from the Extra deck as it changes all monsters to the water Attribute. If your opponent does not play any water monsters this is especially effective, as they will simply be locked into the one monster that you have changed into water with Steatlh Kragen plus the effect of Gozen Match.  *I used a modified version of this deck to climb to Platinum in Master Duel. Since Toadally Awesome is limited to one on Master Duel I substitute the second Toad with Number 47: Nightmare Shark. I also cut 1 Prior of the Ice Barrier, Salvage and Upstart Goblin for 3 Maxx "C" since the extra draw power is absolutely incredible in this deck. If you can find other cards that consistently give you draw power I heavily recommend that you use them in this deck as they help it greatly, both in real life and in Master Duel.

This is a basic synchron deck that I made in Master Duel. I only really added this card because I had one more spot to fill.

While i have loads of nostalgia for this card, i have to admit that i does kind of interfere with my deck.

  - Clear Wing Synchro Dragon

I had this card in the deck before i acquired Crystal Wing and didn't bother to find anything to replace it.

  That's it for now, when i find the cards i'm looking for I'll post an updated list. Any feedback would be appreciated.

deck_excerpt: Masked HERO deck themed around having every single member in it, inspired by Kamen Rider.
deck_description: Masked HERO deck aimed in having every single one of its members, since I'm a Kamen  Rider fan. It wasn't made with competitive play fully in mind so it will most likely struggle against the top meta decks. It was also done in Master Duel specifically so keep it in mind regarding some cards like Maxx C, you might want to change them depending on how and where you're using this.  That being said, some cards were added in the extra deck to make it more survivable like Isolde, Sunrise and Absolute Zero. One of the best combos is to summon Absolute Zero (preferably with Liquid Soldier as one of its materials to activate its effect too) and then Mask Change it to Masked HERO Acid. This will trigger Absolute Zero's Raigeki effect and Acid's Harpie's Feather Duster effect, wiping the opponent's field (provided you're able to do it without negation, of course).  • Don't be afraid to send Shadow Mist to the graveyard, but do be careful when you activate her effect in there. Do not special summon her from the GY on the same turn because you can only activate one effect per turn.  • If you ever use Liquid Soldier's effect to draw 2 cards and have to discard one, and you end up with both a "Change" card and "Mask Charge", discard the "Change" card, you'll be able to recover it immediately with Mask Charge (provided you also have a HERO in the GY).  • Contrast HERO Chaos is the ace of the Masked Heroes and you'll want it as soon as possible.  Any comments for improvements to it are welcome, but keep in mind the theme of the deck is to have every Masked HERO in it in tribute to Kamen Rider.

deck_excerpt: Blue-Eyes Master Duel with Accesscode Talker
deck_description:
• Focus on bring 2 level 8 monsters to the field
    • You can do this by using the effect of the Sage with the Eyes of Blue, Blue-Eyes Alternative White Dragon and Nebula Dragon
  • Summon Number 97: Draglubion, use its effect to summon Number 92: Heart-eartH Dragon using Number 100: Numeron Dragon as material
    • Number 92: Heart-eartH Dragon wipes whatever the opponent built on its turn
    • After this, Number 97: Draglubion can summon Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy and prevents the enemy to activate a spell once per turn
  • Summon Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Dragon and use its rank-up combo to clean the opponent field
    • After summon Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Dragon, use it to summon Galaxy-Eyes Full Armor Photon Dragon and destroy a face-up card on the opponent field
    • After use the effect of Galaxy-Eyes Full Armor Photon Dragon, use it to summon Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Blade Dragon to destroy another card on the opponent field
  • Use Skill Drain if your opponent's deck runs on top of monster effects. Remember that Blue-Eyes it's a boss monster itself.
  • If your opponent have a solid field and if you have battle in your turn with a Xyz Monster, summon Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder to wipe everything at the end of the turn
  • If you have used at least 3 spells, consider using the Accesscode Talker combo
    • First, summon Cryston Halqifibrax. Use its effect to summon a spellcaster turner monster (can be the Sage with Eyes of Blue or the Effect Veiler).
    • Summon Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians and use its effect to summon back the spellscaster monster you've summoned with Cryston Halqifibrax
    • Summon Accesscode Talker tributing Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians, then use its effect targeting Selene on the graveyard to get 5300 of attack power. Also, use its effect to destroy one card your opponent controls.

deck_excerpt: A theorycraft for running the Brave engine in Inzektor despite a bit of anti-synergy.
deck_description: This is an idea I had when opening packs of Grand Creators for some Inzektor stuff.  The Adventure engine is very commonly used in many decks like Prank-kids and PK to insulate combo lines against potential interaction from the opponent, as well as extending combos if no such interaction exists or baiting said interaction if the opponent stops the engine from resolving.  This would hugely benefit Inzektor, which has historically died very hard at certain choke points especially with bad hands and prior to Zektrike Kou-Ou hasn't had very powerful ways to extend through said choke points.  Even if you draw some of the soft garnets in the Brave engine, like Dracoback or Griffon Rider, it's not actually a bad thing.  Dracoback has minor equip synergy with the Inzektors provided you have a way to pop it, and Griffon rider at the very least is a free body to Link with. The problem, however, is the downside inherent in the Adventure engine:  during the turn you resolve Rite of Aramiser, you can't activate the effects of normal summoned monsters.  This is a big problem, considering so many of the classic Inzektor routes revolve around that first normal summon, not to mention the extra normal summon you get from Beetrooper Armor Horn.  Because of this I thought it was a bit disappointing that such anti-synergy exists, considering how much the deck would love to run the engine.  But then I thought maybe they still can.  Yes, there are some hands where you cannot use the brave engine and thus it's more or less dead.  But thanks to Zektrike, there are a lot of 3 or 4 card hands that could allow you to resolve the engine and play through your turn without relying on your Dragonfly or Centepede to be normal summoned, at least not to get effects from doing so.  Additionally, there are many hands where you draw the soft garnets to act as situational extenders.  Heck, there's no penalty for activating Enchantress, so even if your hand can't resolve the brave engine, perhaps just activating Enchantress is enough to make an antsy player burn their Ash.   The brave engine also makes it so even if your hand is utter crap, with no real way to get the Inzektor flow going, just opening Rite or Enchantress is enough to let you end on something. I'm no expert in Inzektors or how well this would work out in practice, but I think it's at least worth testing out.  It's certainly a lot more interesting of a concept than simply replacing the 7 Adventure engine cards with 2 Crossout Designator + 1 of stuff I want to hate on, at least, and I think it should be less bricky too.  What are your thoughts on the concept and the deck ratios?

deck_excerpt: A good mid-range deck to get you started in master duel.
deck_description: Although this is a combo heavy deck, once you understand it's main strategy everything else will come naturally. Your opening plays will ideally start with you using Swirl Slime in the hand with Necro Slime to summon D'Arc, getting at least one other monster on the field (usually by normal summoning a Kepler for a search or a Lamia so you potentially get two uses out of her ideally), using Necro Slime in the gy to bring out Genghis, then linking away D'Arc and your other monster that isn't Genghis to bring out Gilgamesh, set your scales and use Genghis' effect to bring back your D'Arc. After this opening the deck can go in a few directions depending on what you have left in your hand or gy. Brining out Siegfried should be a priority since it's an easy spell/trap negate without an extra cost. Ghost is best used to send back your banished Necro Slimes to the gy by using it for Necro Slime's fusion, he's also a tuner.

deck_excerpt: Lol imagine pendulums playing too defensively
deck_description: Can be played as a mixed aggressive and control. Recycles spells and basically has infinite counter supply.  Servant of Endymion - Can bring out your negates by using 3 spell counters.  Endymion, the Mighty Master of Magic - can basically wipe a field with it's pendulum effect by removing 6 counters. While it's a monster, it's untargetable, and can negate spell/traps  Beast King Jackal - Able to negate monster effects  Master Cerebus - Can search out Jackal and banish opponents monsters. Cannot be destroyed by card effects with 4 or more counters.  Spring of Mysterune - One of the most important card of the decks allowing you to draw 3 cards every turn and activate quick-play spells from your hand.  Point of Mysterune - Searches your cards and banishes your opponents top deck  Munnin - Searches deceit and can be used for link plays, can be used for health gain too  Geri - Recycles field spell and deceit. Also used for link plays or can be used defensively or to destroy monsters  Deck Goal:  Deck out opponent (agressive)  Build up counters and obliterate opponent(control)  -Always keep 1 quick-play spell in your hand if you already used your field spells effect unless in certain situations. You can then use your field spell to recycle more cards and get more quick-play spells on your opponents turn.  -If you plan on going agressive, you still have to play control. It's best to keep your quick-play spells in your hand if you are going this route. This way you can negate with your monsters on board and use your spells when you need them. Works best if your opponent is low on cards and you wiped their field.  -Will always loose to imperial order and has a very tough time against Flundereeze

deck_description: I have 2 ash and 2 droll because i don't like having hand traps x3 that can be used once per turn.  I play 1 invocation because the first game i need 1 invocation only, i would add second invocation for the 2nd and 3rd game but because i main crossout designator really i don't need second invocation.  I main lightning storm because for me the most important turn is my first turn ,doesn't matter if i go second or first,  even if i draw lightning storm other turn i can just use it as material for mechaba  Some players would consider adding Small World but i don't use it, i think 18 starters  for creating a board is enough and i don't need more than that.

deck_excerpt: Rouge Deck to frustrate Master Duel Meta by basically locking up their field
deck_description:
• The main strategy is to bring out either Pachycephalo, Vanitys Fiend or a Barrier Statue (you can change them however you like)
  • Block spell or trap effects with Denko
  • Equip them so they are stronger than any generic level 4
  • Watch your opponents quiver in fear as they are locked out of doing anything
  • You can throw in Vanity's Emptiness if you think it's more consistent
  • The Extra Deck can just be any kind of random Link Monster
 
  • Weaknesses:
    •  Monarchs
    • Spells and (Hand-)Traps
 
  • Any ways I could improve this deck? Let me know in the comments!

deck_name: Laval in Master Duel, is it worth it
deck_excerpt: Pain
deck_description:
Laval is a archetype that is able to play an absolutely ridiculous hyper combo strategy that is pretty similar to synchron, but is much more bricky. It’s an old archetype originating from the synchro era, and it shows, the cards in this deck are very poorly written in both a good way and a bad way.

It’s also a big archetype, meaning it has its own pack, meaning that more of its better cards are supers and ultras, meaning it’s hard to make.

I’ll be replacing sulfer divine with shooting quasar when I get it.

But I, being me, have decided to suffer to make this deck so you don’t have to. And so I did, here’s my list.

Is it worth the amount of resources it requires to make this? No. It isn’t worth it at all.

Feel free to ask me any questions below and I’ll answer to the best of my ability.

deck_excerpt: A Trap deck that Halfs your life for powerful effects.
deck_description:
Dinomorphia aka The Half Deck is a deck that will half your life for powerful Trap cards and Monster Effects.  First the Main Deck.  It is a control deck that is highly corrosive and able to grind for time if needed. The Monsters The main monster in the deck is Dinomorphia Therizia which sets any Dinomorphia trap from deck to the field.  In which you would set Dinomorphia Frenzy and if you already have Frenzy or Domain(Another less powerful Frenzy) you can set any trap needed according to the current game state.  The other Main Deck monster, Dinomorphia Diplos which sends a Dinomorphia trap to the grave to be used for their second effects, be able to recycle itself and Therizia, and or be used with Kentregina.  Both cards float upon destruction by banishing a any trap from GY.  Now the supporting cards.
  • Lord of the Heavenly Prison - To protect your traps and to help set up for next turn if SS(Both it and Ultimate Conductor can be used for an xyz monster)
  • Miscellaneousaurus - To ensure the activation of your Main Monsters
  • Ultimate Conductor Tyranno - A great last resort and Boss Monster if all else goes wrong(Both it and Heavenly Prison can be used for an xyz monster)
  • Flowerdino - An extender and a way to recycle traps and get an extra Special Summon
The Spells There are very few spells and great alternative spells that can be included.  Fossil Dig is a great way to search your Dinomorphia Monsters and if you already have one, to search Misc to ensure they cant be negated.  Pot of Extravagance to draw cards and set up for your opponents turn.  Then Called By the Grave because in a format with loads of Handtraps you need to be able to stop them.  Great alternatives and inclusions are
  • Pot of Prosperity(Other good draw card)
  • Pot of Duality(Also a good draw card)
The Traps Dinomorphia is a heavily Trap reliant deck to be able to control the game.  Cards like Dinomorphia Frenzy and Dinomorphia Domain.  Frenzy is to make Rexstrum and Domain to Make Kentregina and then use its effect to make Rexstrum.  Dinomorphia Brute, which is a non-targeting destruction that destroys your Dinomorphia and one card on their field(Which Dinomorphia is the easy winner cause it can float endlessly)  Dinomorphia Shell, which is a way to stop your opponent from attacking a low Atk Kentregina or Rexstrum by having the opponent have to attack it first.  Also it can be used in pair with Brute for a destruction(Though there wont be a floating effect).  Dinomorphia Sonic, which is just a Spell/Trap negate and destruction.  Lastly Dinomorphia Alert, which Special Summons two Dinomorphia monsters from your GY.  As well, all Dinomorphia Traps have a secondary effect to stop a dangerous situation with burn and attack damage.  Shell and Sonic for Battle damage, and Domain, Frenzy, Brute, and Alert for Effect damage.  Other traps include.
  • The Solemn cards, which lessens your life more for more negates
  • Hope for Escape, which is a great card for drawing more cards later in the game when your life is extremely low
  • Skill Drain, oppressive floodgate that lowers your life by 1000
  • Ferret Flames, a great card that bounces all monsters from the field until the combined attack is less then your life point(aka all of them later in the round)
Extra Deck The Extra Deck is the place everyone will be different because there are so many diverse and good ways to make it, but everyone can agree that three Dinomorphia Rexstrum and Dinomorphia Kentregina is mandatory.  Rexsturm is the best card in the deck and is your main card to get out.  Rexsturm is a walking Skill Drain on legs that hits like a small planet(Hehe Hope for Escape planet joke ahahahahahahaha).  All monsters with less or equal attack to your life points are negated on the field, so DPE and Dragoon are useless and just there.  To help be able to use the effect, it has a second effect to half your life to make the attack of all monsters on the field equal to your life which can be used to otk and or to negate the entire field.  Dinomorphia Kentregina is a monster that halfs your life to imitate a trap in the GY by banishing it.  It has a base attack of 4000, but it never will have 4000 attack.  How it works is that it loses attack up to your life points, so if you have 4000 Life points it has 0 attack, 2000 Life points it has 2000 attack, and so on.  Dinomorphia Stealthbergia, which makes it so if your Life points are under 2000 trap cards that cost life no longer cost life to use, so Solem Strike and Skill Drain can be activated even if you dont have enough Life points to activate it.  Stealthbergia can be at any card limit, but two is the most reasonable in my opinion.  The rest of the Extra deck is heavily customizable.  In my list the Extra Deck monster are.
  • Evolzar  Dolkka, which is a great Monster negate and destruction.
  • Evolzar Laggia, which is a great Spell negate and destruction.
  • Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Gustav Max, which is a way to get game(EVERYONE WOULD KNOW IT WAS A JOKE.  COWBOY FOR GAME IS FOR THE PAST, WE ALL KNOW STALLING FOR TIME AND GUSTAV FOR GAME IS THE NEW ERA).
  • Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Juggernaut Liebe, a big monster to put on Gustav Max for otks.
  • Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder, a way to just wipe boards after attacking with any of the xyz monsters
  • Knightmare Phoenix, a Spell/Trap removal cause you could never have enough removal cards.
Yet just cause I use these cards doesnt mean you have too.  Other great Extra deck Monsters include
  • Abyss Dweller
  • Diagusto Emeral
  • Number 101: Silent Honor ARK
  • Tornado Dragon
  • Number 35: Ravenous Tarantula
  • Number 81: Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Super Dora
There is probably more but those are the ones I considered the most when deck building. For all those who did read this Thank you and I hope you have as much fun with this deck as I will.  If you wanna support me I have a Twitch and YouTube and I might start streaming regularly and post Deck profiles and other fun videos.

deck_name: An Actual Mayakashi Deck (Zombies, but fun!) v2.0
deck_excerpt: Tired of boring meta decks? Sick to the stomach after playing against Eldlich? Then this might be THE zombie deck for you...
deck_description: Mayakashi is my favorite archetype, so seeing decks listed as "Mayakashi" decks with loads of other non-Mayakashi cards in them drives me up a wall. Mayakashis don't need to be paired up with other archetypes like Shiranui or Eldlich (*vomits*) to be good, they can whoop ass all on their own - and here's my deck to prove that. Pretty much every card in this deck is all about helping you combo into your big Mayakashi boss monsters. Will update this deck over time especially when those Mayakashi support cards come over from the OCG to the TCG. -Leo v2.0 Changes  I added a side deck! This strays a bit away from pure Mayakashi bc it involves putting some Danger! cards into the deck. Replace the Uni-Zombies and 1 Dakki if you want to slot the dangers in, and swap the Sunsaga for the Skillsaga. Dangers work pretty great with Mayakashi- they aren't held back by the summoning restrictions, and make your opponent send cards to your GY for absolutely free. Also in the side deck are two copies of Solemn Strike, just in case you need extra negates.

deck_excerpt: A deck focused on the power of Trickstars
deck_description: This deck uses Candina to search either Trickstar lightstage, Trickstar Festival, or Lycoris to then use lightstage to search either Mandrake, Lilybell, or Lycoris. Mandrake is there as fodder. Nightshade is there for 1 off plays if you have nothing in your hand. The traps mainly help Lycoris to deal a ton of dmg. The main play is to get Holly angle to an extra monster zone and get Band sweet guitar & Divardis to a zone that Holly angle points too.

deck_excerpt: Dragonmaids, but also your monsters are my materials
deck_description: This is a versatile deck featuring Fallen of Albaz as the star of the show. Dragonmaids are used as an all around good engine, but also to disguise what the deck is capable of. If the opponent uses their disruption on the Dragonmaids, they are more vulnerable to a Fallen of Albaz.  On a Dragonmaid start, the deck may play like a typical Dragonmaid deck and end the turn on a Sheou. It is also capable of linking up to Accesscode Talker and bringing out a Borreload Savage Dragon later.  On a Windwitch start, the turn ends on a Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon. From here there's a fun detour to take if you have your single copy of Magicalized Fusion, where you can bring out one of the spellcaster link monsters in order to summon Quintet Magician. He's nothing crazy, but the fact that he can't be Kaiju'd or fusioned away makes me happy.  On a start where you have access to Fallen of Albaz, you just feel out how the opponent will try to disrupt you, bait it out if you can, and then fusion their best monster away with Albion the Branded Dragon, Starving Venom Fusion Dragon, or Mudragon of the Swamp. Super Polymerization will also allow you to summon Albaz and then use Sprind the Irondash Dragon on your opponent's turn to use any one of the opponent's effect monsters as fusion material.
